{"title_page": "Ruslan Chagaev", "text_new": "{{short description|Uzbekistani boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Ruslan Chagaev<br>{{small|\u0420\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0427\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432}}\n| image = RuslanChagaev.jpg{{!}}border\n| caption = Chagaev in 2007\n| realname = {{nowrap|Ruslan Shamilevich Chagaev}}\n| nickname = White [[Mike Tyson|Tyson]]\n| nationality = [[Uzbekistan]]i\n| height = 1.85 m\n| reach = 188 cm\n| weight = [[Heavyweight]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1978|10|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Andijan]], [[Uzbek SSR]], [[Soviet Union]] (now Uzbekistan)\n| style = [[Southpaw (boxing)|Southpaw]]\n| total = 38\n| wins = 34\n| KO = 21\n| losses = 3\n| draws = 1\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry | {{UZB}} }}\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[amateur boxing]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Amateur Boxing Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1997 World Amateur Boxing Championships|1997 Budapest]] | Heavyweight}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2001 World Amateur Boxing Championships|2001 Belfast]] | Super-heavyweight}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Junior Boxing Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | 1996 Havana | Heavyweight}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Boxing at the Asian Games|Asian Games]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[Boxing at the 1998 Asian Games|1998 Bangkok]] | [[Boxing at the 1998 Asian Games \u2013 Men's 91 kg|Heavyweight]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Amateur Boxing Championships|Asian Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[1999 Asian Amateur Boxing Championships|1999 Tashkent]] | Heavyweight}}\n}}\n\n'''Ruslan Shamilevich Chagaev''' ({{lang-tt|\u0420\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b \u0443\u043b\u044b \u0427\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432/Ruslan \u015eamil ul\u0131 \u00c7a\u011fayev}}; {{lang-uz|Ruslan Shamil'evich Chagaev}}; {{lang-ru|\u0420\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0428\u0430\u043c\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0427\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432}}); born 19 October 1978) is a retired [[Uzbekistan|Uzbek]] [[professional boxer]] of [[Tatar]]ian descent who competed from 2001 to 2016. He held the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[heavyweight]] title twice, from 2007 to 2009 and from 2014 to 2016, and was the first Asian boxer to win a world heavyweight title by any of the four major sanctioning bodies.\n\nChagaev is one of a few professional boxers to resume his [[Amateur boxing|amateur]] career after a few professional bouts in 1997. Chagaev was reinstated as an amateur by [[AIBA]] the following year as his professional bouts were declared [[exhibition fight|exhibitions]].\n\nIn 2007, Chagaev defeated then-unbeaten [[Nikolai Valuev]] to win his first WBA heavyweight title, and would make two successful defences. Due to injuries and being unable to grant Valuev a rematch in 2009, the WBA stripped Chagaev of the title. He went on to suffer his first professional loss in the same year to unified heavyweight champion [[Wladimir Klitschko]].\n\nChagaev won the [[WBA (Regular)]] heavyweight title by defeating [[Fres Oquendo]] in 2014. He made one successful defence, then lost the title to [[Lucas Browne]] in 2016. However, after Browne [[doping in sport|failed a drug test]], the WBA reinstated Chagaev as champion, but he was once again stripped of the title in July after failing to pay sanctioning fees. On 28 July 2016 he announced his retirement from boxing due to ongoing eye injuries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allboxing.ru/news/20160728-0832/smi-ruslan-chagaev-reshil-zavershit-kareru-iz-za-problem-s-glazami|title=\u0421\u041c\u0418: \u0420\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0427\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0448\u0438\u043b \u0437\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0448\u0438\u0442\u044c \u043a\u0430\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0440\u0443 \u0438\u0437-\u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c \u0441 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=July 28, 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nAs an amateur, Chagaev won gold medals at the [[2001 World Amateur Boxing Championships|2001 World Championships]] and [[1999 Asian Amateur Boxing Championships|1999 Asian Championships]], in the heavyweight and [[super-heavyweight]] divisions respectively.\n\n==Amateur career==\nChagaev won gold at the [[1997 World Amateur Boxing Championships]] heavyweight, defeating [[F\u00e9lix Sav\u00f3n]] in the finals, but later he was stripped of the championship for having 2 professional bouts in the United States before the tournament. Chagaev is the only non-Cuban boxer to defeat F\u00e9lix Sav\u00f3n twice, and the only one to do it at the world championships, which Sav\u00f3n have won consecutively. Sav\u00f3n suffered his first international defeat in more than a decade, when he met Chagaev for a first time.<ref>[https://gleaner.newspaperarchive.com/kingston-gleaner/1997-10-26/page-47/ Cuba\u2019s Savon beaten] (Reuters,) ''Kingston Gleaner'', October 26, 1997, p. 47.</ref> His amateur career is also merited with absence of stoppages on his part, with all four his losses were standing defeats with him being outpointed.\n\n===Highlights===\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{{gold1}} [[1995 Asian Amateur Boxing Championships|Asian Championships]] (91&nbsp;kg), [[Tashkent, Uzbekistan]], October 1995:\n*1/8: Defeated [[Jiang Tao (boxer)|Jiang Tao]] (China) 11\u20134\n*1/4: Defeated Talgat Dossanov (Kazakhstan) 12\u20136\n*1/2: Defeated Bahman Azizpour (Iran) 20\u20134\n*Finals: Defeated [[Lakha Singh (boxer)|Lakha Singh]] (India) 16\u20131\n{{gold1}} Uzbek National Spartakiade (91&nbsp;kg), [[Tashkent, Uzbekistan]], January 1996:\n*Finals: (no data available)\n[[Boxing at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Heavyweight|Summer Olympics]] (91&nbsp;kg), [[Atlanta, Georgia]], July 1996:\n*1/16: Lost to [[Luan Krasniqi]] (Germany) 4\u201312\n{{bronze3}} [[World Junior Boxing Championships|World Junior Championships]] (91&nbsp;kg), [[Havana, Cuba]], November 1996:\n*1/4: Defeated [[Marat Tovmasian]] (Armenia) RSC 3\n*1/2: Lost to Yurkis Sterling (Cuba) 11\u201314\n{{gold1}} Trofeo Italia (+81&nbsp;kg), [[Naples, Italy]], March 1997:\n*Finals: Defeated [[Giacobbe Fragomeni]] (Italy) walkover\n{{gold1}} Usti Grand Prix (91&nbsp;kg), [[Usti nad Labem, Czech Republic]], March 1997:\n*Finals: Defeated Vladimir Lazebnik (Ukraine) RSC 1\n{{gold1}} King's Cup (91&nbsp;kg), [[Bangkok, Thailand]], April 1997:\n*1/4: Defeated Waipramong Puiloh (Thailand) walkover\n*1/2: Defeated Harpal Singh (India) RSC 2\n*Finals: Defeated Talgat Dossanov (Kazakhstan) RSCH 3\n{{gold1}} [[1997 World Amateur Boxing Championships|World Championships]] (91&nbsp;kg), [[Budapest, Hungary]], October 1997:\n*1/8: Defeated [[Sergey Dychkov]] (Belarus) 15\u20137 (5 rds)\n*1/4: Defeated [[Giacobbe Fragomeni]] (Italy) 18\u20134 (5 rds)\n*1/2: Defeated Maik Hanke (Germany) 12\u20137 (5 rds)\n*Finals: Defeated [[F\u00e9lix Sav\u00f3n]] (Cuba) 14\u20134 (5 rds)\n:{{small|On February 8, 1998, AIBA stripped the championship of Chagaev for having 2 professional bouts in the United States before the tournament.}}\n{{gold1}} [[Boxing at the 1998 Asian Games \u2013 Men's 91 kg|Asian Games]] (91&nbsp;kg), [[Bangkok, Thailand]], December 1998:\n*1/4: Defeated Hitra Bahadur (Nepal) RSCH 1\n*1/2: Defeated [[Rouhollah Hosseini]] (Iran) 17\u20132\n*Finals: Defeated Muzaffar Iqbal Mirza (Pakistan) RSCH 1\n{{Col-2}}\n{{gold1}} [[Strandzha Cup]] (91&nbsp;kg), [[Plovdiv, Bulgaria]], February 1999:\n*Finals: Defeated [[F\u00e9lix Sav\u00f3n]] (Cuba) 7\u20132 (4 rds)\n{{gold1}} French Open (91&nbsp;kg), [[Calonne-Ricouart]] - [[Berck-sur-Mer]] - [[Gravelines]], [[France]], May 1999:\n*1/4: Defeated Reynald Zolnierczyk (France) RET 2\n*1/2: Defeated [[Sergey Dychkov]] (Belarus) 10\u20130\n*Finals: Defeated [[Giacobbe Fragomeni]] (Italy) 3\u20132\n[[1999 World Amateur Boxing Championships|World Championships]] (91&nbsp;kg), [[Houston, Texas]], August 1999:\n*1/16: Defeated [[Garth da Silva]] (New Zealand) 9\u20133 (4 rds)\n*1/8: Defeated David Turner (Australia) RSC 3\n*1/4: Lost to [[F\u00e9lix Sav\u00f3n]] (Cuba) 1\u20139 (4 rds)\n{{gold1}} [[1999 Asian Amateur Boxing Championships|Asian Championships]] (91&nbsp;kg), [[Tashkent, Uzbekistan]], October 1999:\n*1/4: Defeated Ma Jing Wei (China) RSC 1\n*1/2: Defeated [[Rouhollah Hosseini]] (Iran) 13\u20135\n*Finals: Defeated Talgat Dossanov (Kazakhstan) 14\u20130\n{{gold1}} Ahmet C\u00f6mert Memorial (91&nbsp;kg), [[Istanbul, Turkey]], April 2000:\n*1/2: Defeated Mehmet Hendem (Turkey) (4 rds)\n*Finals: Defeated [[Odlanier Sol\u00eds]] (Cuba) 4\u20133 (4 rds)\n[[Boxing at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Heavyweight|Summer Olympics]] (91&nbsp;kg), [[Sydney, Australia]], September 2000:\n*1/8: Defeated [[Oleksandr Yatsenko (boxer)|Oleksandr Yatsenko]] (Ukraine) 15\u20132\n*1/4: Lost to [[Vladimir Chanturia]] (Georgia) 12\u201318\n{{gold1}} Ahmet C\u00f6mert Memorial (+91&nbsp;kg), [[Istanbul, Turkey]], April-May 2001:\n*1/8: Defeated Wajid M'Barki (Tunisia)\n*1/4: (no data available)\n*1/2: Defeated Mehdi Aouiche (France)\n*Finals: Defeated [[Oleksiy Mazikin]] (Ukraine) RET 2\n{{gold1}} [[2001 World Amateur Boxing Championships|World Championships]] (+91&nbsp;kg), [[Belfast, Northern Ireland]], June 2001:\n*1/8: Defeated Rustam Rygebayev (Kazakhstan) RSCO 3\n*1/4: Defeated Csaba Kurtucz (Hungary) RSCO 2\n*1/2: Defeated [[Vitali Boot]] (Germany) RSCO 3\n*Finals: Defeated [[Oleksiy Mazikin]] (Ukraine) RSCO 2\n{{Col-end}}\nChagaev had a few professional bouts while competing as an amateur. He finished his amateur career having a total of 85 fights under his belt, with a record of 81 wins, 4 losses (no stoppages.)\n\n==Professional career==\n===1997\u20132005: Early career ===\n\n[[File:Ruslan Chagaev MUC-20060108.jpg|thumb|180px|Ruslan Chagaev (center) inside the ring with his coach [[Michael Timm]] (right) challenging [[Rob Calloway]] (left). 7 January 2006).]]\n\nHaving fought twice in 1997, Chagaev returned to amateur boxing. He turned pro fully in 2001, with the only flaw on his early record coming 5 October 2002 bout against [[Rob Calloway]] in [[Detroit, Michigan]], United States. At the end of third round, the fight was stopped due to Calloway having a wound caused by a headbutt. Michigan boxing rule mandated that the fight be called a Technical Draw (TD) since the bout ended by an accidental foul. Usually four rounds are needed to go to the score cards for decision.\n\nChagaev slowly but steadily climbed up the heavyweight ranks, first avenging the no-contest with a brutal second-round knockout of Calloway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ringside24.com/en/bout/1001/|title=Ruslan Chagaev - Rob Calloway|work=ringside24.com|access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref>\n\n===2006: Title contender===\n\nIn 2006 he beat undefeated Ukrainian prospect [[Vladimir Virchis]] in a close and intense punchfest, and slowly took apart prominent British boxer [[Michael Sprott]].\n\nOn 18 November 2006, he fought the former WBA champion [[John Ruiz]], and prevailed in a close contest. He took a split decision with scores of 117\u2013111 and 116\u2013112 for Chagaev, and 115\u2013114 for Ruiz. Chagaev became the [[mandatory challenger]] for a shot at [[Nikolai Valuev]], the WBA heavyweight champion at the time. Valuev was sat ringside and believed Chagaev was the rightful winner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.uzreport.uz/news_10_e_23497.html|title=Ruslan Chagaev beats John Ruiz to earn WBA heavyweight title shot - UzReport.uz|last=UzReport|website=news.uzreport.uz|access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132009: WBA heavyweight champion ===\n\n====Chagaev vs. Valuev====\nThe fight between Chagaev and WBA titlist Valuev took place on 14 April 2007 at the [[Porsche-Arena]] in [[Stuttgart]], Germany. Chagaev won the fight and WBA title via a majority decision (117\u2013111, 115\u2013113 and 114\u2013114). Many ringside had the fight close and some calling it controversial.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxing247.com/news/Valuev-Chagaev.php|title=Nikolai Valuev vs Ruslan Chagaev: Boxing Results|website=www.boxing247.com|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref> With the win, Chagaev became the first Asian to win a world heavyweight title.\n\nOn 26 June 2007, it was announced that Chagaev would partake in a heavyweight unification bout with [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] heavyweight champion [[Sultan Ibragimov]]. The fight was due to take place in Moscow on 13 October 2007 and would have been the first heavyweight unification bout since 1999;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=2917159|title=ESPN \u2013 Ibragimov, Chagaev to unify heavyweigh titles \u2013 Boxing|accessdate=2007-06-28}}</ref> however, Chagaev had to drop out of the fight after contracting [[Homologous serum jaundice|hepatitis B]].<ref name='USA TODAY 2007-12-06'>{{cite news | agency=Associated Press| title=Skelton to face Chagaev for WBA heavyweight title | date=6 December 2007| publisher=Gannett Co. Inc. | url =https://www.usatoday.com/sports/boxing/2007-12-06-wba-heavyweights_N.htm | work =USA TODAY | accessdate = 2002-02-16}}</ref> At that point, it was not clear whether he would have been able to compete at all, with WBA considering a championship tournament for Chagaev's crown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=11989&more=1|title=Boxing Commentary: The WBA Tournament \u2013 Are These Guys Crazy?|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013132425/http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=11989&more=1|archivedate=13 October 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> After Ibragimov defended his crown against [[Evander Holyfield]], however, it was announced that Chagaev was able to recover.\n\n==== Chagaev vs. Skelton ====\nChagaev made his first official defence against Commonwealth heavyweight champion [[Matt Skelton]] (21-1, 18 KOs) on 19 January 2008 at the Burg-Waechter Castello in [[D\u00fcsseldorf]]. Skelton's promoter [[Frank Warren (promoter)|Frank Warren]] initially wanted the fight to take place in February or March, but Chagaev insisted an earlier date. In regards to fighting Skelton, Chagaev said, \"I am completely healthy and I am ready to fight, I want to get in the ring. It will be a hard fight against a good puncher.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/fights/chagaev-skelton.html|title=Chagaev Skelton: Ruslan Chagaev vs Matt Skelton|website=www.boxingscene.com|access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref> The fight was marred with a series of illegal tactics initiated by Skelton, many of them resembling techniques used in [[Muay Thai]] and [[kickboxing]] matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ENWfojW39wo|title=2008 01 19 Ruslan Chagaev vs Matt Skelton\n|website=youtube.com|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> Chagaev retained his WBA title via unanimous decision, with the judges scoring the fight 117-110, 117-111 and 117-111 in Chagaev's favour.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/7179677.stm|title=BBC SPORT {{!}} Boxing {{!}} Skelton fails in world title bid|website=news.bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/2289464/Ruslan-Chagaev-denies-Matt-Skelton-world-title.html|title=Ruslan Chagaev denies Matt Skelton world title|last=Lewis|first=By Mike|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis next mandatory defense was to be a rematch on 5 July 2008 with Nikolai Valuev, who defeated former WBO champion [[Sergei Liakhovich]] by unanimous decision to earn the right. However, the fight had to be cancelled after Chagaev suffered a complete tear of an [[Achilles tendon]] during his final sparring session in preparation for the defense, causing Chagaev's second postponement of the match. The WBA elected to make Chagaev \"Champion in Recess\" due to the injury that Chagaev sustained and necessary recovery time and mandated that top-contenders Valuev and John Ruiz meet for the vacated title. By beating Ruiz, Valuev also became champion on 30 August 2008.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/may/29/boxing-chagaev-valuev|title=Injury forces Ruslan Chagaev out of fight with Nikolai Valuev|date=2009-05-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==== Chagaev vs. Drumond ====\nChagaev returned from injury on 7 February 2009 to fight the then-unbeaten Costa Rican [[Carl Davis Drumond]]. For the fight, Chagaev was not listed as WBA champion, but rather the \"Champion in Recess\". The fight took place at the StadtHalle in [[Rostock]]. Chagaev sustained a cut from an unintentional clash of heads in the third round. The fight ended after round 6, with Chagaev winning the fight via technical decision. Chagaev was taken to hospital after the fight for treatment. Judge Jean-Louis Legland had Chagaev ahead 60-54, whilst judges Hector Afu and Paul Thomas had Chagaev ahead 58-56.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=3891427|title=Chagaev beats Drumond on technical decision|date=2009-02-07|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref>\n\nChagaev and Valuev were supposed to fight no later than 26 June 2009 to determine who the WBA regarded as their champion.<ref>[http://www.notifight.com/artman2/publish/Resultado_2/Chagaev_venci_a_Davis_Drummond_en.php \u00a1Chagaev venci\u00f3 a Davis Drummond en Rostock!]. Notifight.com. Retrieved on 2011-04-19.</ref> They were scheduled to fight on 30 May 2009 in Helsinki, Finland at the [[Hartwall Arena]], but Chagaev failed a Finnish medical test, allegedly due to hepatitis.\n\n==== Chagaev vs. Klitschko ====\n{{Main|Wladimir Klitschko vs. Ruslan Chagaev}}\n[[Wladimir Klitschko]] (52-3, 46 KOs) was scheduled to face [[David Haye]], who pulled out within weeks of the fight complaining of a back injury. Salvaging the 20 June 2009 date and venue, Klitschko instead faced Chagaev. The winner would take the vacant ''[[The Ring (magazine)|Ring]]'' magazine heavyweight title in the battle between their number 1 ranked heavyweight, Klitschko, and third ranked Chagaev.  Klitschko was defending his [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]], [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] and [[International Boxing Organization|IBO]] heavyweight titles. Chagaev's [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] champion in recess title was not on the line. There were 61,000 fans in attendance at the [[Veltins-Arena|Veltins Arena]]. Klitschko controlled the tempo of the fight from the very beginning and hit Chagaev at will with the jab. He hit Chagaev with several hard right crosses and never allowed him to build momentum. Towards the end of the second round Klitschko caught Chagaev off-balance and sent him to the canvas. Chagaev recovered but was dominated thereafter. After an onslaught of punches towards the end of the ninth round Chagaev retired  after the round. This win had added significance because, even though the WBA and WBC titles were not on the line, Ring magazine and many others saw Klitschko as the rightful champion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/sports/boxing/news/story?id=4274889|title=Klitschko wins by TKO, keeps heavyweight titles|date=2009-06-20|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/jun/20/wladimir-klitschko-defeats-ruslan-chagaev|title=Wladimir Klitschko knocked out Ruslan Chagaev to retain his WBO and IBF world heavyweight titles|date=2009-06-20|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Winfred Monroe|title=Wladimir Klitschko vs. Ruslan Chagaev Full Fight|date=2016-10-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YVGq8pDB9m0|accessdate=2017-09-28}}</ref> On 24 July 2009, when the WBA published their Official Ratings as of June 2009, Chagaev was no longer the \"Champion in Recess\" but the No. 1 challenger instead.\n\n=== 2010\u201311: Regaining composure ===\n\nChagaev fought [[Kali Meehan]] (35\u20133, 29 KO) on 22 May 2010, in a WBA heavyweight title eliminator at the Stadthalle in [[Rostock]], Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Germany.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/boxing/7751421/Ruslan-Chagaev-to-fight-Kali-Meehan-for-chance-to-face-David-Haye.html|title=Ruslan Chagaev to fight Kali Meehan for chance to face David Haye|last=Correspondent|first=By Gareth A Davies, Boxing|work=Telegraph.co.uk|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en}}</ref> Chagaev won the bout by unanimous decision with the scores of 117\u2013111, 117\u2013112 and 118\u2013110.<ref>{{cite web\n  | last =Sukachev\n  | first =Alexey\n  | title =Chagaev Decisions Meehan, David Haye Could Be Next\n  | work =\n  | publisher =BoxingScene.com\n  | date =22 May 2010\n  | url =http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=27999\n  | accessdate =23 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2010/5/22/1483561/ruslan-chagaev-beats-kali-meehan|title=Ruslan Chagaev beats Kali Meehan in Germany|date=2010-05-22|website=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref> Six months later in a stay-busy fight, he defeated [[Travis Walker]] via unanimous decision in an eight-round fight which turned into a slugfest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxnews.com.ua/en/news/7924/2010-11-20/Ruslan-Chagaev-Barely-Beats-Travis-Walker-in-a-Brawl|title=Ruslan Chagaev Barely Beats Travis Walker in a Brawl - World boxing - Boxing news - BOXNEWS.com.ua|website=www.boxnews.com.ua|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/522850-ruslan-chagaev-edges-travis-walker-in-heavyweight-slugfest-wba-champ-haye-next|title=Ruslan Chagaev Edges Travis Walker in Heavyweight Slugfest: WBA Champ Haye Next?|last=Walker|first=Johnny|work=Bleacher Report|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== Chagaev vs. Povetkin ====\nAfter [[Wladimir Klitschko]] unified his WBO and IBF titles with [[David Haye]]'s WBA title, Klitschko was upgraded to \"Super Champion\" by the WBA, thus making the \"Regular Champion\" title vacant.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/klitschkos-trainer-not-happy-with-povetkin-chagaev--43076|title=Klitschko's Trainer Not Happy With Povetkin-Chagaev|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en-us}}</ref> On 6 July 2011 negotiations for Chagaev to fight undefeated [[Alexander Povetkin]] (22-0, 15 KOs) for the vacant title began between Sauerland, who promote Povetkin, and Chagaev's promoter Universum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/povetkin-vs-chagaev-negotiations-wba-title-fight--41200|title=Povetkin vs Chagaev Negotiations For WBA Title Fight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en-us}}</ref> Two days later, Povetkin's trainer confirmed the fight would take place on 27 August.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/povetkin-chagaev-confirmed-by-teddy-atlas-aug-27--41301|title=Povetkin-Chagaev Confirmed By Teddy Atlas For Aug. 27|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en-us}}</ref> With Atlas in his corner, Povetkin bested Chagaev by unanimous decision to capture the WBA (Regular) heavyweight title at the Messehalle arena in [[Erfurt|Erfurt, Germany]]. The judges scored the bout 117\u2013113, 117\u2013113 and 116\u2013112 all in favor of Povetkin.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/alexander-povetkin-beats-ruslan-chagaev-wins-wba-belt--43083|title=Alexander Povetkin Beats Ruslan Chagaev, Wins WBA Belt|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-27|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.badlefthook.com/2011/8/27/2388537/povetkin-vs-chagaev-results-unanimous-decision-wba-heavyweight-title|title=Povetkin vs Chagaev Results: Povetkin Picks Up WBA Belt With Unanimous Decision Win|date=2011-08-27|website=Bad Left Hook|access-date=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n\n===2012\u201316: WBA Regular champion ===\n\nAfter the Povetkin bout, Chagaev went 5-0 (3 KO), defeating world ranked Jovo Pudar & four journeymen with respectable records.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/drozd-stops-masternak-chagaev-chakhkiev-win--70290|title=Drozd Stops Masternak: Chagaev and Chakhkiev Win|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 2013, at a press conference in [[Sofia|Sofia, Bulgaria]], European heavyweight champion [[Kubrat Pulev]] (17-0, 9 KOs) stated his plans to fight Chagaev next although details had not been discussed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/pulev-vs-chagaev-close-august-24th-showdown--66648|title=Pulev vs. Chagaev is Close For August 24th Showdown|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> Towards the end of the month, Chagaev spoke out denying any rumours that he was interested in a fight with Pulev. He instead stated that he was closing in on a deal to fight undefeated Cuban [[Luis Ortiz (Cuban boxer)|Luis Otiz]] (19-0, 16 KOs) in the fall of 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/ruslan-chagaev-eyes-luis-ortiz-scrap-not-kubrat-pulev--67152|title=Ruslan Chagaev Eyes Luis Ortiz Scrap, Not Kubrat Pulev|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==== Chagaev vs. Oquendo ====\nIn May 2014, talks began for a fight between Chagaev and former world title challenger [[Fres Oquendo]] (37-7, 24 KOs) for the vacant WBA \"regular\" heavyweight title in June. Oquendo climbed the WBA rankings further after stopping Galen Brown (41-27-1, 24 KOs) in two rounds earlier in the month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/fres-oquendo-ruslan-chagaev-talks-june-7th--77767|title=Fres Oquendo-Ruslan Chagaev in Talks For June 7th|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> Oquendo pulled out in July due to passport issues and was on the verge of being replaced by German boxer [[Alexander Petkovic]] (49-4-4, 27 KOs), however Oquendo managed to board a plane, confirming the bout was still on.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/photo-oquendo-on-plane-back-with-chagaev--79558|title=Photo: Oquendo on The Plane, Back in With Chagaev|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> The fight took place on 6 July at the [[Akhmat-Arena|Ahmat Arena]] in Grozny. Chagaev claimed the vacant title via majority decision after 12 rounds in a tough battle. Judge Guillermo Perez Pineda scored the fight 114-114, whilst judges Gustavo Jarquin and Alexis Marin both scored it 115-113 in favour of Chagaev, giving him the win. Chagaev controlled most of the fight with his constant jab and later in the fight started connecting with body shots.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/chagaev-edges-oquendo-capture-wba-crown--79612|title=Chagaev Edges Oquendo To Capture The WBA Crown|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnewsonline.net/ruslan-chagaev-edges-fres-oquendo-in-farcical-world-title-bout/|title=Ruslan Chagaev edges Fres Oquendo in farcical \u2018world\u2019 title bout - Boxing News|date=2014-07-07|work=Boxing News|access-date=2017-03-25|language=en-US}}</ref> A few days after the fight, the WBA ordered Chagaev vs. Ortiz. Both camps had 30 days to negotiate a deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/ruslan-chagaev-luis-ortiz-ordered-by-wba--82772|title=Ruslan Chagaev-Luis Ortiz is Ordered By The WBA|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Oquendo spoke out about not receiving his guaranteed purse of $1 million and an immediate rematch within 120 days if he lost. His promoters Hitz Boxing and Square Ring Promotions, who were guaranteed an additional $100,000 were also reportedly not paid. Bobby Hitz of Hitz Boxing stated that they would file a lawsuit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/fres-oquendo-stiffed-1-million-from-chagaev-fight--84177|title=Fres Oquendo Stiffed For $1 Million From Chagaev Fight|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> In the same month, RUSADA released information from a mandatory drug test that was taken after the fight which stated that Oquendo had tested positive for [[Tamoxifen|tamoxifin]] and [[anastrozole]]. According to the fight contract, this meant Oquendo would need to pay back his purse.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/report-oquendo-failed-drug-test-from-chagaev-bout--84625|title=Report: Oquendo Failed Drug Test From Chagaev Bout|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> In December, a $5 million lawsuit was filed by Oquendo against promoter Terek Box Event seeking damages caused by the agreement to the Federal Court in Manhattan. In a statement, Oquendo said, \u201cI am really looking forward to my day in court and finally getting justice. These guys pulled a really slick move and tricked me into fighting on July 6 by promising me to increase my purse to $1 million and giving me a rematch at a time when I wasn't mentally right, with my wife and newborn baby being sick and in the hospital. Well, now they are the ones behind the eight ball. They\u2019ve got until January 2 to respond to the lawsuit.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/oquendo-files-5-million-lawsuit-against-terek-box-event--85354|title=Oquendo Files $5 Million Lawsuit Against Terek Box Event|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> In April 2015, the judges issued an injunction.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/chagaevs-title-run-on-hold-judge-issues-injunction--89461|title=Chagaev's Title Run on Hold After Judge Issues Injunction|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n====Chagaev vs. Pianeta====\n\nIn May 2015, it was announced that Chagaev would make his first title defense against long time contender WBA #13 [[Francesco Pianeta]] (31-1, 17 KOs) on 11 July at the [[GETEC Arena]] in [[Magdeburg|Magdeburg, Germany]]. Pianeta's only loss came in 2013 to Wladimir Klitschko via stoppage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingnews24.com/2015/05/ruslan-chagaev-vs-francesco-pianeta-on-july-11th-in-germany/|title=Ruslan Chagaev vs. Francesco Pianeta on July 11th in Germany \u00bb Boxing News|date=2015-05-10|work=Boxing News 24|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/chagaev-pianeta-title-clash-set-7-11-magdeburg--90777|title=Chagaev-Pianeta Title Clash Set, 7/11 In Magdeburg|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> World of Boxing president Andrey Ryabinsky helped settle the issue between Chagaev and Oquendo. With the legal battle finished, it was said that Oquendo would fight the winner of Chagaev vs. Pianeta.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/ryabinsky-helps-end-chagaev-oquendo-legal-dispute--91887|title=Ryabinsky Helps End Chagaev-Oquendo Legal Dispute|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> Chagaev won the fight via 1st-round TKO. Pianeta was dropped with two lefts but beat the 10 count. He was then dropped again following two more lefts. Referee Jean-Louis Legland stopped the fight 3 seconds before the round was due to end.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/13240202/ruslan-chagaev-floors-francesco-pianeta-1st-round-keep-wba-title|title=Chagaev defends WBA title with 1st-round TKO|work=ESPN.com|access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/ruslan-chagaev-destroys-francesco-pianeta-one--93386|title=Ruslan Chagaev Destroys Francesco Pianeta in One - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|language=en-us|access-date=2017-09-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/9910627/ruslan-chagaev-stops-francesco-pianeta-to-retain-wba-title|title=Ruslan Chagaev stops Francesco Pianeta to retain WBA title|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=BlackLionDE|title=Ruslan Chagaev vs. Francesco Pianeta (Full Fight) Ko 1.Runde Ganzer Kampf Knockout|date=2015-07-11|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v_ldTmRE3QM|accessdate=2017-03-25}}</ref>\n\nChagaev and Oquendo were scheduled to have their rematch on 17 October at the [[Sparkassen-Arena|Sparkassen Arena]] in Kiel, Germany. On 6 October, Oquendo pulled out of the fight citing illness.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/oquendo-withdraws-from-ruslan-chagaev-title-rematch--96634|title=Oquendo Withdraws From Ruslan Chagaev Title Rematch|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n==== Chagaev vs. Browne ====\nOn 14 November 2015, the WBA ordered Chagaev to reach a deal to make a defence of his WBA title against Australian heavyweight contender [[Lucas Browne]]. The two sides had until 30 November to reach a deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/chagaev-reach-deal-with-lucas-browne-by-11-30--98139|title=Chagaev Must Reach Deal With Lucas Browne By 11/30|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> Chagaev's promoter Timur Dugazaev announced the fight would likely take place in [[Grozny]] in March 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/ruslan-chagaev-lucas-browne-eyed-february-march--98755|title=Ruslan Chagaev-Lucas Browne Eyed For February, March|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> In the January 2016, the fight was officially announced to take place on 5 March.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/lucas-browne-promises-top-form-chagaev-title-clash--100209|title=Lucas Browne Promises Top Form For Chagaev Title Clash|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref> Browne won the fight by stopping Chagaev in the tenth round. Browne landed nearly 20 unanswered punches, mostly right hands, before referee [[Stanley Christodoulou]] stopped the fight at 2 minutes, 27 seconds. Browne was knocked down in the sixth round and at the time of the knockout, behind on all judges scorecards (81-88, 82-88 twice).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10194276/lucas-browne-stops-ruslan-chagaev-to-become-wba-world-heavyweight-champion|title=Lucas Browne stops Ruslan Chagaev to become WBA world heavyweight champion|work=Sky Sports|access-date=2017-09-28|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/browne-gets-off-floor-knocks-chagaev-out-wba-belt--102078|title=Browne Gets Off The Floor, Knocks Chagaev Out For WBA Belt|work=BoxingScene.com|access-date=2017-12-29|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported on March 22 that Browne failed his post-fight drug test and was then stripped of the belt and will likely have the result changed to a no-decision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/15035971/lucas-browne-failed-drug-test-fight-vs-ruslan-chagaev|title=Browne failed drug test after fight vs. Chagaev|website=ESPN.com|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/boxing/news/12183/10279911/lucas-browne-stripped-of-wba-title-after-positive-b-test|title=Browne Stripped & Banned|last=|first=|date=May 13, 2016|website=Sky Sports|publisher=|access-date=May 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 28, it was reported that Chagaev had been stripped of his WBA 'Regular' title for failure to pay outstanding sanctioning fees. According to WBA, Chagaev and promoter Timur Dugazaev have repeatedly failed to pay $40,750 in sanctioning fees related to Chagaev's majority decision victory against [[Fres Oquendo]]. The WBA said it sought payment multiple times and had no choice but to vacate the title when there was no response.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/boxing/story/_/id/17147189/ruslan-chagaev-stripped-heavyweight-title-wba-failure-pay-sanctioning-fees|title=WBA strips Chagaev of heavyweight title belt|access-date=2016-07-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Retirement ===\nIt was announced on 28 July 2016 by manager Timur Dugashev that Chagaev announced his retirement from boxing at the age of 37 due to problems with his eyes. Dugashev stated: \"Ruslan informed us that he would no longer fight. The reason is the state of his eyes. Health is the most important thing.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.meganewsweb.com/en/news/breaking-news-znamenityj-bokser-ruslan-chagaev-zavershil-kareru|title=MEGA NEWS {{!}} Latest news {{!}} The famous boxer Ruslan Chagaev retired|website=www.meganewsweb.com|access-date=2016-07-28}}</ref>\n\nThere was reports in October 2016 that Chagaev was offered a farewell fight to close his career, potentially a rematch with Lucas Browne. Chagaev chose to stay retired due to health issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/ruslan-chagaev-rejects-farewell-fight-intends-stay-retired--109811?|title=Ruslan Chagaev Rejects Farewell Fight, Intends To Stay Retired - Boxing News|website=www.boxingscene.com|access-date=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nChagaev is of [[Volga Tatars|Volga Tatar]] ethnicity and an adherent of [[Islam]].<ref name=\"fakty.ua\">{{cite web|url=http://fakty.ua/19798-rodnaya-sestra-ruslana-chagaeva-luiza-gorzhus-chto-moj-brat-ni-razu-v-zhizni-ne-vykuril-ni-odnoj-sigarety-i-ne-prigubil-spirtnogo|title=\u0420\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430 \u0440\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0447\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430 \u043b\u0443\u0438\u0437\u0430: \u00ab\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0436\u0443\u0441\u044c, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442 \u043d\u0438 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0443 \u0432 \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0438 \u043d\u0435 \u0432\u044b\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0438\u043b \u043d\u0438 \u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439...|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ummahsports.net/2015/06/10/top-10-active-muslim-boxers/|title=Top 10 active Muslim boxers|date=June 10, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> His parents, Shamil and Zamira Chagaev, are [[Mishar Tatars]] from the village of Kalda<ref name=\"fakty.ua\" /> (located in today's [[Baryshsky District]] of [[Ulyanovsk Oblast]], Russia), who moved to the [[Uzbek Soviet Socialist Republic|Uzbek SSR]] in the 1950s.<ref name=\"fakty.ua\" /> Chagaev has a sister, Luiza.<ref name=\"fakty.ua\" /> He is married to Viktoria, an ethnic [[Armenians|Armenian]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sovsport.ru/gazeta/article-item/259754|title=\u0427\u0435\u043c\u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 WBA \u0420\u0443\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d \u0427\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0435\u0432 (\u0423\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d): \u0422\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435 \u0431\u043e\u044f \u044f \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0433\u043b\u044f\u0434\u0435\u043b, \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0436\u0435 \u0412\u0430\u043b\u0443\u0435\u0432 \u043e\u0433\u0440\u043e\u043c\u043d\u044b\u0439!|work=\u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442}}</ref> who is also from Andijan. They have three children together: Artur, Alan and Adam. Their first son, Artur, was born on 24 March 2004. Ruslan resides in [[Hamburg]], Germany with his family.\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=1\n|ko-wins=21\n|ko-losses=2\n|dec-wins=13\n|dec-losses=1\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|38\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|34\u20133\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Lucas Browne]]\t\n|TKO\n|10 (12), {{small|2:02}}\n|5 Mar 2016\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|RUS}} {{small|Colosseum Sport Hall, Grozny, Russia}}\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{small|Lost WBA (Regular) heavyweight title;<br>Chagaev later reinstated as champion after Browne failed a drug test}}\n|-\n|37\n|{{yes2}}Win\n|34\u20132\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Francesco Pianeta]]\t\n|TKO\n|1 (12), {{small|2:57}}\n|11 Jul 2015\n|sty