o Wallin}}\n{{s-bef|before=Jovo Pudar}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Pan Asian Boxing Association|PABA]] heavyweight champion\n|years=5 October 2013 \u2013 5 July 2014<br>Vacated}}\n{{s-vac|next=[[Joseph Parker (boxer)|Joseph Parker]]}}\n{{s-text|style=background:#C1D8FF; font-weight: bold;|text=World boxing titles}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Nikolai Valuev]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of WBA world champions#Heavyweight|WBA heavyweight champion]]\n|years=14 April 2007 \u2013 18 July 2008<br>Status changed}}\n{{s-vac|next=Nikolai Valuev}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-vac|last=[[Alexander Povetkin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=WBA heavyweight champion<br>[[WBA (Regular)|Regular title]]\n|years=6 July 2014 \u2013 5 March 2016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lucas Browne]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=Lucas Browne<br>Stripped}}\n{{s-ttl|title=WBA heavyweight champion<br>Regular title\n|years=13 May 2016 \u2013 25 July 2016<br>Stripped}}\n{{s-vac|next=[[Manuel Charr]]}}\n{{s-text|style=background:#C1D8FF; font-weight: bold;|text=Honorary boxing titles}}\n{{s-new}}\n{{s-ttl|title=WBA heavyweight champion<br>In recess\n|years=18 July 2008 \u2013 [[Wladimir Klitschko vs. Ruslan Chagaev|20 June 2009]]<br>Stripped}}\n{{s-non|reason=Title discontinued}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Footer World Amateur Champions Super Heavyweight}}\n{{Footer Asian Games Champions Boxing Heavyweight}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chagaev, Ruslan}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1996 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 2000 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Super-heavyweight boxers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistani Muslims]]\n[[Category:Volga Tatars]]\n[[Category:Tatar people]]\n[[Category:Tatar sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Southpaw boxers]]\n[[Category:World Boxing Association champions]]\n[[Category:World heavyweight boxing champions]]\n[[Category:People from Andijan]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in boxing]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1998 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games competitors for Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Uzbekistani male boxers]]\n[[Category:AIBA World Boxing Championships medalists]]\n[[Category:Asian Games gold medalists for Uzbekistan]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1998 Asian Games]]\n", "name_user": "IvanchukW", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision viewership", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruslan_Chagaev"}
{"title_page": "Hazel O'Connor", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name           = Hazel O'Connor\n| image          = Hazel O Connor.jpg\n| caption        = O'Connor in 2010 at the Ropetackle Centre, Shoreham\n| image_size     =\n| background     = solo_singer\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=y|1955|5|16}}\n| birth_place    = [[Coventry]], England\n| occupation     = Singer-songwriter, actress\n| genre          = [[New wave music|New wave]], [[Alternative rock|alternative]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[New-age music|new-age]]\n| associated_acts=\n| website        = {{URL|www.hazeloconnor.com}}\n}}\n'''Hazel O'Connor''' (born 16 May 1955<ref>{{Allmusic | class = artist | id = p110545 | tab = biography | label = Biography of Hazel O'Connor | first = Steve | last = Leggett | accessdate = September 2009 }}</ref>) is a British singer-songwriter and actress. She became famous in the early 1980s with [[hit single]]s \"[[Eighth Day (Hazel O'Connor song)|Eighth Day]]\", \"D-Days\" and \"[[Will You? (Hazel O'Connor song)|Will You?]]\", as well as starring in the film ''[[Breaking Glass]]''.<ref name=\"Edinburgh News\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/whats-on/entertainment/hazel-o-connor-talks-beyond-breaking-glass-1-3053912|title=Hazel O'Connor talks Beyond Breaking Glass|website=www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nO'Connor was born in [[Coventry]], [[England]]. She is the daughter of a soldier from [[Galway]] who settled in England after the Second World War to work in a car plant.\n\nHer film debut was in ''Girls Come First'' in 1975.<ref name=\"auto\">{{IMDb title|id=0187065|title=Girls Come First}}</ref> She became prominent as an actress and singer five years later in 1980 when playing the role of Kate in the film ''[[Breaking Glass]]'', and performing its accompanying soundtrack.\n\n{{Quote|text=I ran away from my home in Coventry when I was 16.....made and sold clothes in Amsterdam, picked grapes in France, joined a dance troupe that went to Tokyo then onto Beirut (escaping the start of the civil war by one month!) traveled West Africa, crossed the Sahara, sang with a dreadful singing trio for the U.S. troops in Germany and came home to \"settle down\". Through all this experience of life and the world I realized that singing always cheered me up. I decided to be a singer. Through strange turns of fate I ended up in a film called 'Breaking Glass' I also ended up writing all the songs for the movie.|sign=Hazel O'Connor|source=''introduction note of the program for a gig at \"At My Place\" in Santa Monica, CA, 1989<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rescuerooms.com/gig-guide/234/hazel-oconnor|title=The Rescue Rooms \u2013 Hazel O'Connor live at The Rescue Rooms|website=www.rescuerooms.com}}</ref>}}\n\nHer performance as Kate won her the [[Variety Club of Great Britain]] Award for 'Best Film Actor'. She was also nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Music]]. The [[Breaking Glass (album)|film's soundtrack album]] featured songs written and performed by O'Connor and reached number 5 in the [[UK Albums Chart]]. It had a 38-week chart run and was certified Gold by the British Phonographic Industry.<ref>[https://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx BPI online database] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917112745/https://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |date=17 September 2016 }}</ref> Several tracks from the album were released as singles, the most successful being \"Eighth Day\" and \"Will You\" (with a notable saxophone solo by Wesley Magoogan<ref>{{cite web |title=The little-known musicians behind some of music's most famous moments |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/oct/21/little-known-musicians-famous-moments-baker-street |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=18 August 2018 |language=en |date=21 October 2014}}</ref>) which both reached the UK Top 10. When O'Connor toured the UK to promote the album, the opening act were a then-unknown group called [[Duran Duran]]. It was the band's first opportunity to play to large audiences throughout the UK and gave them the exposure they needed to secure a recording contract.\n\nSubsequent albums released by O'Connor included ''Sons and Lovers'' (which featured the UK Top 10 hit single \"D Days\"), ''Cover Plus'', ''Smile'', ''Private Wars'' and ''Five in the Morning''. O'Connor also collaborated with other artists, and made appearances in the video for [[Mick Karn]]'s \"The Sound Of Waves\" and a cameo appearance in the 1983 [[Eurythmics]] video \"[[Who's That Girl? (Eurythmics song)|Who's That Girl?]]\".\n\nO'Connor donated her songwriting talents to [[Greenpeace|Greenpeace First International Record Project]] released worldwide in 1985 as a response to the French bombing and subsequent sinking of the ''[[Rainbow Warrior (1955)|Rainbow Warrior]]''. Her duet song \"Push and Shove\" with [[Chris Thompson (English musician)|Chris Thompson]] leads off the second act of the album and accompanying video.\n\nShe has made numerous television appearances, starring in ''Jangles'' on British television and in 1986 playing the lead role of Vivienne in ''Fighting Back'' as well as singing the theme tune. She also played a singer in an episode of [[Prospects (TV series)|''Prospects'']] on [[Channel 4]] in 1986 resulting in the release of two spin-off singles alongside former ''Breaking Glass'' actor [[Gary Olsen]]. For a time she was interested in becoming a member of [[The International Society for Krishna Consciousness]], commonly known as the Hare Krishna movement, and starred in a 60-minute film about her relationship with the Krishnas titled ''Persuaders'' which was broadcast by the [[BBC]] in December 1985.<ref>Nori J. Muster, \"Betrayal of the Spirit,\" (University of Illinois Press: 1997), 126.</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hare Krishna in the Movies|title=UK Channel 4 - The Persuaders (1986) (Entire TV Documentary)|date=2017-11-06|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZ9HpweO6zY&t=16s|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\nHer theatre work included ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (play)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]], ''Nightshoot'' at the Tricycle Theatre, London, ''Girlfriends'' at the Playhouse, London, ''Swing Out Sister'', her own production, at the Riverside Studio, London, ''The Raven Beckons'' at the Riverbank Theatre, Dublin and ''The Cuchulain Cycle'' at the Riverside Studio, London.\n\nIn 1997 she recorded the studio album ''Five in the Morning'' with record producer, co-writer and guitarist, Gerard Kiely. The album included the song \"Na Na Na\". A [[live album]], ''Live in Berlin'', followed.\n\nThe turn of the century saw O'Connor tell her life story in a touring show entitled ''Beyond Breaking Glass'', with [[harpist]] [[Cormac de Barra]]. The show was a hit at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in 1998<ref>[http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/what-s-on/theatre/theatre-review-beyond-breaking-glass-1-3057953 The Scotsman Theatre review: Beyond Breaking Glass] 22 August 2013</ref> and toured the UK, the Netherlands (twice), Australia and Canada.\n\nShe signed to [[Invisible Hands Music]] in 2002; this triggered a run of new releases and of deluxe re-issues of her 1990s work. A commercially available reincarnation of the previously [[mail-order]] ''Beyond the Breaking Glass'' was followed by a previously unreleased acoustic concert, ''Acoustically Yours''.\n\nIn 2003, Invisible Hands Music released O'Connor's first-ever official best of [[compilation album|compilation]], ''A Singular Collection'', which brought together her early hits from the Albion days, mid career work at RCA, and the best of the latter, DIY era. To add something new to the best of compilation, O'Connor recorded a [[cover version|cover]] of her friend [[George Michael]]'s hit \"One More Try\", with a band that included drummer [[Carlos Hercules]], who at the time was playing for [[Annie Lennox]] and [[Beverley Knight]]. Hercules joined George Michael's band in 2006. The track was released as a single, and generated extensive airplay and renewed interest in O'Connor\u2014the following year saw her perform at the [[Glastonbury Festival]].\n\n''Hidden Heart'', produced by [[Martin Rushent]] and including [[duet (music)|duets]] with [[Maire Brennan]] and [[Rob Reynolds (musician)|Rob Reynolds]], was released in the UK in 2006, and her 1984 album ''Smile'' was reissued on CD in 2008.\n\nIn 2008, O'Connor performed for the second time at the [[Glastonbury Festival]], playing an acoustic set on the Avalon stage.\n\nIn 2009, O'Connor performed as part of the '1980s Here and Now' tour at many venues including Wembley Arena.{{citation needed|date=September 2009}} She continued to tour extensively with her own solo projects, 'Beyond the Breaking Glass' and 'Bluja Project'. In 2009 she was awarded her own star on Coventry's 'Walk of Fame'.\n\nIn September 2010, O'Connor performed in France with The Bluja Project featuring Clare Hirst and Sarah Fisher, and in Ireland in October with Cormac de Barra. She then performed 'Breaking Glass Live' throughout England, culminating in a show at the [[Leicester Square Theatre]] in London on 5 December 2010.\n\nOn 25 June 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Hazel O&#39;Connor among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=28 June 2019 |date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nO'Connor married artist Kurt Bippert in 1987. The ceremony took place on [[Venice Beach, California|Venice Beach]], [[California]]. It received coverage by ''[[Hello!]]'' magazine. The actor [[David Rappaport]] was [[Groomsman|best man]], and [[Dave Wakeling]] from [[The Beat (British band)|The Beat]] gave O'Connor away. Bippert and O'Connor divorced in 2000.\n\nShe had previously dated [[Hugh Cornwell]]<ref>Cornwell, Hugh. ''A Multitude of Sins: The Autobiography'', HarperCollins, 2004. {{ISBN|0007438249}}</ref> and [[Midge Ure]].<ref>Midge Ure's autobiography, ''If I Was''</ref>\n\nO'Connor is a vegetarian.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vegsoc.org/vegmag/Hazel%20O_11.pdf |title=Last Word \u2013 Hazel O'Connor |publisher=[[Vegetarian Society]] |work=The Vegetarian magazine |year=2003 |accessdate=18 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011191009/http://www.vegsoc.org/vegmag/Hazel%20O_11.pdf |archivedate=11 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nHer brother Neil fronted the punk band [[The Flys (UK band)|The Flys]], best known for their single \"Love and a Molotov Cocktail\", which she later [[cover version|covered]].\n\nO'Connor currently divides her time between living in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] and France. She is friends with BBC Radio London host [[JoAnne Good]] and singer [[Toyah Willcox]], whom she narrowly beat for the lead role in ''Breaking Glass''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.ie/regionals/goreyguardian/lifestyle/a-life-of-walking-on-broken-glass-27336130.html |title=A life of walking on broken glass |publisher=Independent.ie |date=21 July 2010 |accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''[[Breaking Glass (album)|Breaking Glass]]'' (1980) No.&nbsp;5 [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]\n*''Sons And Lovers'' (1980)\n*''Cover Plus'' (1981) No.&nbsp;32 UK\n*''Smile'' (1984)\n*''Greatest Hits'' (1984)\n*''Alive And Kicking in L.A.'' (1990)\n*''To Be Freed'' (1993)\n*''Over The Moon...Live'' (1993)\n*''See The Writing on the Wall'' (1993)\n*''Private Wars'' (1995)\n*''Live in Berlin'' (1997)\n*''5 in the Morning'' (1998)\n*''Beyond the Breaking Glass'' (2000)\n*''L.A. Confidential \u2013 Live'' (2000)\n*''Acoustically Yours'' (2002)\n*''Ignite'' (2002)\n*''A Singular Collection \u2013 The Best of Hazel O'Connor'' (2003)\n*''D-Days'' (2003)\n*''Hidden Heart'' (2005)\n*''Fighting Back \u2013 Live in Brighton'' (2005)\n*''Smile 2008'' (2008)\n*''The Bluja Project'' (2010)<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited\n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 403}}</ref>\n*''Breaking Glass Now'' (2010)\n*''I Give You My Sunshine'' (2011)\n*''Here She Comes'' (2014)\n*''Access All Areas'' (2016)\n*''See You Again'' (2017)\n*''Hallelujah Moments'' (2018)\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Ee-I-Adio\" (1979)\n*\"Writing on the Wall\" (1980)\n*\"[[Eighth Day (Hazel O'Connor song)|Eighth Day]]\" (1980) No.&nbsp;5 [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n*\"Give Me An Inch\" (1980) No.&nbsp;41 [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n*\"Time\" (1980)\n*\"Waiting/Sons And Lovers\" (1980) (Australia Only)\n*\"D-Days\" (1981) No.&nbsp;10 UK\n*\"[[Will You (Hazel O'Connor song)|Will You]]\" (1981) No.&nbsp;8 UK\n*\"Zoo\" (1981) (Germany Only)\n*\"Do What You Gotta Do/Waiting\" (1981) (Not UK)\n*\"(Cover Plus) We're All Grown Up\" (1981) No.&nbsp;41 [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n*\"Hanging Around\" (1981) No.&nbsp;45 [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n*\"Calls the Tune\" (1982) No.&nbsp;60 [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n*\"Men of Good Fortune/D-Days (New Version)\" (1982) (Flexipop Release)\n*\"That's Life\" (1982)\n*\"Don't Touch Me\" (1984) No.&nbsp;81 [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n*\"Just Good Friends\" (1984)\n*\"Tell Me a Story Now/The Man I Love\" (1984)\n*\"Cuts Too Deep\" (1984)\n*\"Stranger in a Strange Land\" (1985)\n*\"Why Don't You Answer\" (1985)\n*\"Push and Shove\" (1985) with [[Chris Thompson (English musician)|Chris Thompson]]\n*\"Fighting Back\" (1986)\n*\"Today Could Be So Good\" (1986)\n*\"We Tried Boy (Didn't We?)\" (1986)\n*\"And I Dream\" (1987) with [[David Easter]]\n*\"Heat of the Night\" (1990)\n*\"My Friend Jack\" (1993)\n*\"Tell Me Why\" (1993)\n*\"All I've Been Missing\" (1995) \n*\"Na, Na, Na\" (1998)\n*\"One More Try\" (2004)\n*\"I'll See You Again\" / \"Hidden\" (2005) with [[Moya Brennan]])\n*\"(World Stops) Spinning Without You\" (2010) with [[Subterraneans (band)|The Subterraneans]]<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/>\n\nAlso featured on:\n*\"[[Let It Be (Ferry Aid song)|Let It Be]]\" ([[MS Herald of Free Enterprise|Zeebrugge Ferry Disaster]] charity ensemble) (No.&nbsp;1 UK) (1987)\n*\"The Wishing Well\" ([[Great Ormond Street Hospital]] charity ensemble) (No.&nbsp;22 UK) (1987)\n*\"Rap Against Rape (What Did I Do Wrong)\" (\"Jocks & Co\" charity single) (No.&nbsp;16 IE) (1990)\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!Year\n!Film\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1975\n|''Girls Come First'' <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|Claire\n|Comedy short by ''Joseph McGrath'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0569825|title=Joseph McGrath}}</ref>\n|-\n|1977\n|''Double Exposure'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0292495|title=Double Exposure}}</ref>\n|Shirley\n|Thriller by ''William Webb'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=1034647|title=William Webb}}</ref>\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Breaking Glass|Breaking Glass]]'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0080469|title=Breaking Glass}}</ref>\n|Kate\n|Drama Musical by ''Brian Gibson'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0001270|title=Brian Gibson}}</ref> - [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FKLp8Y5RlQ8 Official Film Trailer]\n|-\n|1982\n|''Jangles'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0376403|title=Jangles}}</ref>\n|Joanne\n|TV mini series (7 episodes) by ''HTV West'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0032564|title=HTV West}}</ref> \n|-\n|1983\n|\"[[Who's That Girl? (Eurythmics song)|Who's That Girl?]]\"\n|Herself\n|Music video (Eurythmics)\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Prospects (TV series)|Prospects]]''  <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0134259|title=Prospects}}</ref>\n|Bev Reid\n|TV series (Episode 10 - Follow the Yellow Brick Lane) by ''Euston Films'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0103398|title=Euston Films}}</ref> - [https://www.imdb.com/video/vi2073863705?playlistId=tt0134259&ref_=tt_ov_vi Official Series Trailer]\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Car Trouble (film)|Car Trouble]]'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0088883|title=Car Trouble}}</ref>\n|Maureen\n|Comedy by ''David Green'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0337765|title=David Green}}</ref>\n|-\n|1986\n|''Fighting Back'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0421336|title=Fighting Back}}</ref> \n|Viv Sharpe\n|TV mini series (5 episodes) by ''British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC)'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0043107|title=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC)}}</ref>\n|-\n|1990\n|''Alive and Kicking in L.A.''\n|Herself\n|Documentary\n|-\n|2005\n|''Hazel O'Connor Live in Brighton'' \n|Herself\n|Live DVD including interview\n|-\n|2008\n|''Beyond The Breaking Glass'' \n|Herself\n|A limited release documenting O'Connor's life story in the style of her stage show ''Beyond The Breaking Glass''\n|-\n|2019\n|''Baghdad In My Shadow'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=6864088|title=Baghdad In My Shadow}}</ref>\n|Kate\n|Thriller by ''Samir'' <ref>{{IMDb title|id=0759848|title=Samir}}</ref> - [https://www.imdb.com/video/vi777632793?ref_=tt_pv_vi_aiv_1 Official Film Trailer] - [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dOYIjG_NaKM Preview of Kate Forever performing Wakey Wakey]\n|}\n\n==Books==\n*\"Breaking Glass Barefoot - The Autobiography\" (2012)\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.hazeloconnor.com}}\n* [https://www.facebook.com/pg/HazelOConnorOfficial Hazel O'Connor on Facebook]\n* [https://twitter.com/Hazel_oconnor Hazel O'Connor on Twitter]\n* [https://instagram.com/hazeloconnorofficial Hazel O'Connor on Instagram]\n* {{youtube|user=hazeloconnor}}\n* [https://www.pinterest.com/hocofficial/ Hazel O'Connor on Pinterest]\n* [https://hazeloconnor.tumblr.com/ Hazel O'Connor on Tumblr]\n* [https://www.songkick.com/artists/431851-hazel-oconnor Hazel O'Connor on Songkick]\n* [https://www.ents24.com/uk/tour-dates/hazel-oconnor Hazel O'Connor on Ents24]\n* [https://www.reverbnation.com/hazeloconnorofficial Hazel O'Connor on Reverbnation]\n* [https://www.bandsintown.com/HazelO'connor Hazel O'Connor on Bandsintown]\n* {{IMDb name|id=0640351|name=Hazel O'Connor}}\n* {{AllRovi person|id=53356|name=Hazel O'Connor}}\n* [https://www.hazeloconnor.net/ Hazel O'Connor Fansite]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oconnor, Hazel}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English female singers]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Coventry]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Music in Coventry]]\n[[Category:Female new wave singers]]\n[[Category:English new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:Musicians from the West Midlands (county)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name           = Hazel O'Connor\n| image          = Hazel O Connor.jpg\n| caption        = O'Connor in 2010 at the Ropetackle Centre, Shoreham\n| image_size     =\n| background     = solo_singer\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|df=y|1955|5|16}}\n| birth_place    = [[Coventry]], England\n| occupation     = Singer-songwriter, actress\n| genre          = [[New wave music|New wave]], [[Alternative rock|alternative]], [[Folk music|folk]], [[New-age music|new-age]]\n| associated_acts=\n| website        = {{URL|www.hazeloconnor.com}}\n}}\n'''Hazel O'Connor''' (born 16 May 1955<ref>{{Allmusic | class = artist | id = p110545 | tab = biography | label = Biography of Hazel O'Connor | first = Steve | last = Leggett | accessdate = September 2009 }}</ref>) is a British singer-songwriter and actress. She became famous in the early 1980s with [[hit single]]s \"Eighth Day\", \"D-Days\" and \"Will You\", as well as starring in the film ''[[Breaking Glass]]''.<ref name=\"Edinburgh News\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/whats-on/entertainment/hazel-o-connor-talks-beyond-breaking-glass-1-3053912|title=Hazel O'Connor talks Beyond Breaking Glass|website=www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nO'Connor was born in [[Coventry]], [[England]]. She is the daughter of a soldier from [[Galway]] who settled in England after the Second World War to work in a car plant.\n\nHer film debut was in ''Girls Come First'' in 1975.<ref name=\"auto\">{{IMDb title|id=0187065|title=Girls Come First}}</ref> She became prominent as an actress and singer five years later in 1980 when playing the role of Kate in the film ''[[Breaking Glass]]'', and performing its accompanying soundtrack.\n\n{{Quote|text=I ran away from my home in Coventry when I was 16.....made and sold clothes in Amsterdam, picked grapes in France, joined a dance troupe that went to Tokyo then onto Beirut (escaping the start of the civil war by one month!) traveled West Africa, crossed the Sahara, sang with a dreadful singing trio for the U.S. troops in Germany and came home to \"settle down\". Through all this experience of life and the world I realized that singing always cheered me up. I decided to be a singer. Through strange turns of fate I ended up in a film called 'Breaking Glass' I also ended up writing all the songs for the movie.|sign=Hazel O'Connor|source=''introduction note of the program for a gig at \"At My Place\" in Santa Monica, CA, 1989<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rescuerooms.com/gig-guide/234/hazel-oconnor|title=The Rescue Rooms \u2013 Hazel O'Connor live at The Rescue Rooms|website=www.rescuerooms.com}}</ref>}}\n\nHer performance as Kate won her the [[Variety Club of Great Britain]] Award for 'Best Film Actor'. She was also nominated for the [[BAFTA Award for Best Film Music]]. The [[Breaking Glass (album)|film's soundtrack album]] featured songs written and performed by O'Connor and reached number 5 in the [[UK Albums Chart]]. It had a 38-week chart run and was certified Gold by the British Phonographic Industry.<ref>[https://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx BPI online database] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917112745/https://www.bpi.co.uk/certified-awards.aspx |date=17 September 2016 }}</ref> Several tracks from the album were released as singles, the most successful being \"Eighth Day\" and \"Will You\" (with a notable saxophone solo by Wesley Magoogan<ref>{{cite web |title=The little-known musicians behind some of music's most famous moments |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/oct/21/little-known-musicians-famous-moments-baker-street |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=18 August 2018 |language=en |date=21 October 2014}}</ref>) which both reached the UK Top 10. When O'Connor toured the UK to promote the album, the opening act were a then-unknown group called [[Duran Duran]]. It was the band's first opportunity to play to large audiences throughout the UK and gave them the exposure they needed to secure a recording contract.\n\nSubsequent albums released by O'Connor included ''Sons and Lovers'' (which featured the UK Top 10 hit single \"D Days\"), ''Cover Plus'', ''Smile'', ''Private Wars'' and ''Five in the Morning''. O'Connor also collaborated with other artists, and made appearances in the video for [[Mick Karn]]'s \"The Sound Of Waves\" and a cameo appearance in the 1983 [[Eurythmics]] video \"[[Who's That Girl? (Eurythmics song)|Who's That Girl?]]\".\n\nO'Connor donated her songwriting talents to [[Greenpeace|Greenpeace First International Record Project]] released worldwide in 1985 as a response to the French bombing and subsequent sinking of the ''[[Rainbow Warrior (1955)|Rainbow Warrior]]''. Her duet song \"Push and Shove\" with [[Chris Thompson (English musician)|Chris Thompson]] leads off the second act of the album and accompanying video.\n\nShe has made numerous television appearances, starring in ''Jangles'' on British television and in 1986 playing the lead role of Vivienne in ''Fighting Back'' as well as singing the theme tune. She also played a singer in an episode of [[Prospects (TV series)|''Prospects'']] on [[Channel 4]] in 1986 resulting in the release of two spin-off singles alongside former ''Breaking Glass'' actor [[Gary Olsen]]. For a time she was interested in becoming a member of [[The International Society for Krishna Consciousness]], commonly known as the Hare Krishna movement, and starred in a 60-minute film about her relationship with the Krishnas titled ''Persuaders'' which was broadcast by the [[BBC]] in December 1985.<ref>Nori J. Muster, \"Betrayal of the Spirit,\" (University of Illinois Press: 1997), 126.</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Hare Krishna in the Movies|title=UK Channel 4 - The Persuaders (1986) (Entire TV Documentary)|date=2017-11-06|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NZ9HpweO6zY&t=16s|access-date=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\nHer theatre work included ''[[One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest (play)|One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest]]'' at the [[Royal Exchange, Manchester]], ''Nightshoot'' at the Tricycle Theatre, London, ''Girlfriends'' at the Playhouse, London, ''Swing Out Sister'', her own production, at the Riverside Studio, London, ''The Raven Beckons'' at the Riverbank Theatre, Dublin and ''The Cuchulain Cycle'' at the Riverside Studio, London.\n\nIn 1997 she recorded the studio album ''Five in the Morning'' with record producer, co-writer and guitarist, Gerard Kiely. The album included the song \"Na Na Na\". A [[live album]], ''Live in Berlin'', followed.\n\nThe turn of the century saw O'Connor tell her life story in a touring show entitled ''Beyond Breaking Glass'', with [[harpist]] [[Cormac de Barra]]. The show was a hit at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] in 1998<ref>[http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/what-s-on/theatre/theatre-review-beyond-breaking-glass-1-3057953 The Scotsman Theatre review: Beyond Breaking Glass] 22 August 2013</ref> and toured the UK, the Netherlands (twice), Australia and Canada.\n\nShe signed to [[Invisible Hands Music]] in 2002; this triggered a run of new releases and of deluxe re-issues of her 1990s work. A commercially available reincarnation of the previously [[mail-order]] ''Beyond the Breaking Glass'' was followed by a previously unreleased acoustic concert, ''Acoustically Yours''.\n\nIn 2003, Invisible Hands Music released O'Connor's first-ever official best of [[compilation album|compilation]], ''A Singular Collection'', which brought together her early hits from the Albion days, mid career work at RCA, and the best of the latter, DIY era. To add something new to the best of compilation, O'Connor recorded a [[cover version|cover]] of her friend [[George Michael]]'s hit \"One More Try\", with a band that included drummer [[Carlos Hercules]], who at the time was playing for [[Annie Lennox]] and [[Beverley Knight]]. Hercules joined George Michael's band in 2006. The track was released as a single, and generated extensive airplay and renewed interest in O'Connor\u2014the following year saw her perform at the [[Glastonbury Festival]].\n\n''Hidden Heart'', produced by [[Martin Rushent]] and including [[duet (music)|duets]] with [[Maire Brennan]] and [[Rob Reynolds (musician)|Rob Reynolds]], was released in the UK in 2006, and her 1984 album ''Smile'' was reissued on CD in 2008.\n\nIn 2008, O'Connor performed for the second time at the [[Glastonbury Festival]], playing an acoustic set on the Avalon stage.\n\nIn 2009, O'Connor performed as part of the '1980s Here and Now' tour at many venues including Wembley Arena.{{citation needed|date=September 2009}} She continued to tour extensively with her own solo projects, 'Beyond the Breaking Glass' and 'Bluja Project'. In 2009 she was awarded her own star on Coventry's 'Walk of Fame'.\n\nIn September 2010, O'Connor performed in France with The Bluja Project featuring Clare Hirst and Sarah Fisher, and in Ireland in October with Cormac de Barra. She then performed 'Breaking Glass Live' throughout England, culminating in a show at the [[Leicester Square Theatre]] in London on 5 December 2010.\n\nOn 25 June 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Hazel O&#39;Connor among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=28 June 2019 |date=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nO'Connor married artist Kurt Bippert in 1987. The ceremony took place on [[Venice Beach, California|Venice Beach]], [[California]]. It received coverage by ''[[Hello!]]'' magazine. The actor [[David Rappaport]] was [[Groomsman|best man]], and [[Dave Wakeling]] from [[The Beat (British band)|The Beat]] gave O'Connor away. Bippert and O'Connor divorced in 2000.\n\nShe had previously dated [[Hugh Cornwell]]<ref>Cornwell, Hugh. ''A Multitude of Sins: The Autobiography'', HarperCollins, 2004. {{ISBN|0007438249}}</ref> and [[Midge Ure]].<ref>Midge Ure's autobiography, ''If I Was''</ref>\n\nO'Connor is a vegetarian.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vegsoc.org/vegmag/Hazel%20O_11.pdf |title=Last Word \u2013 Hazel O'Connor |publisher=[[Vegetarian Society]] |work=The Vegetarian magazine |year=2003 |accessdate=18 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011191009/http://www.vegsoc.org/vegmag/Hazel%20O_11.pdf |archivedate=11 October 2007 }}</ref>\n\nHer brother Neil fronted the punk band [[The Flys (UK band)|The Flys]], best known for their single \"Love and a Molotov Cocktail\", which she later [[cover version|covered]].\n\nO'Connor currently divides her time between living in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] and France. She is friends with BBC Radio London host [[JoAnne Good]] and singer [[Toyah Willcox]], whom she narrowly beat for the lead role in ''Breaking Glass''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.ie/regionals/goreyguardian/lifestyle/a-life-of-walking-on-broken-glass-27336130.html |title=A life of walking on broken glass |publisher=Independent.ie |date=21 July 2010 |accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''[[Breaking Glass (album)|Breaking Glass]]'' (1980) No.&nbsp;5 [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]\n*''Sons And Lovers'' (1980)\n*''Cover Plus'' (1981) No.&nbsp;32 UK\n*''Smile'' (1984)\n*''Greatest Hits'' (1984)\n*''Alive And Kicking in L.A.'' (1990)\n*''To Be Freed'' (1993)\n*''Over The Moon...Live'' (1993)\n*''See The Writing on the Wall'' (1993)\n*''Private Wars'' (1995)\n*''Live in Berlin'' (1997)\n*''5 in the Morning'' (1998)\n*''Beyond the Breaking Glass'' (2000)\n*''L.A. Confidential \u2013 Live'' (2000)\n*''Acoustically Yours'' (2002)\n*''Ignite'' (2002)\n*''A Singular Collection \u2013 The Best of Hazel O'Connor'' (2003)\n*''D-Days'' (2003)\n*''Hidden Heart'' (2005)\n*''Fighting Back \u2013 Live in Brighton'' (2005)\n*''Smile 2008'' (2008)\n*''The Bluja Project'' (2010)<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\">{{cite book\n| first= David\n| last= Roberts\n| year= 2006\n| title= British Hit Singles & Albums\n| edition= 19th\n| publisher= Guinness World Records Limited\n| location= London\n| isbn= 1-904994-10-5\n| page= 403}}</ref>\n*''Breaking Glass Now'' (2010)\n*''I Give You My Sunshine'' (2011)\n*''Here She Comes'' (2014)\n*''Access All Areas'' (2016)\n*''See You Again'' (2017)\n*''Hallelujah Moments'' (2018)\n\n===Singles===\n*\"Ee-I-Adio\" (1979)\n*\"Writing on the Wall\" (1980)\n*\"[[Eighth Day (Hazel O'Connor song|Eighth Day]]\" (1980) No.&nbsp;5 [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n*\"Give Me An Inch\" (1980) No.&nbsp;41 [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n*\"Time\" (1980)\n*\"Waiting/Sons And Lovers\" (1980) (Australia Only)\n*\"D-Days\" (1981) No.&nbsp;10 U