{"title_page": "Eric Gilder", "text_new": "'''Eric Gilder''' (25 December 1911 \u2013 1 June 2000) was an [[England|English]] [[musicology|musicologist]], and also a [[teacher]], [[Conducting|conductor]], [[composer]] and [[pianist]]. He was best known as the principal of the Eric Gilder School of Music.\n\n==Biography==\nGilder was a pupil at [[Henry Thornton Grammar School|Henry Thornton School]] in Clapham from 1926 until 1931, and composed the original school song.<ref>[http://www.oldthorntoniansclapham.org.uk/page8.htm Old Thorntonians Association]</ref> He initially studied mathematics and physics, but in 1936 he gained a scholarship to the [[Royal College of Music]] where he studied under [[John Ireland (composer)|John Ireland]], [[Ralph Vaughan Williams]], [[Constant Lambert]] and Sir [[Malcolm Sargent]]. He continued there until interrupted by war service.<ref name=gilder>[http://www.musicweb-international.com/Classpedia/Gilder.htm The 'Eric Gilder' entry from his own ''Dictionary of Composers and Their Music'' (1985)]</ref>\n\nAfter the war he worked variously as a pianist, conductor and broadcaster, and as principal of his own school of music. He began his career as a teacher at the Central School of Dance Music at 15 [[West Street, London|West Street]] in London. This was originally established in 1950 by jazz guitarist [[Ivor Mairants]], primarily for jazz, big band and popular music players. Mairants handed the school over to Gilder in 1960 and it became the Eric Gilder School of Music.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DGuvAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA232&lpg=PA232&dq=%22central+school+of+dance+music%22&source=bl&ots=0sn4VQxKtf&sig=ACfU3U1A4Iju8xPSIejucoiNs1pfsFVOfQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjzwey1-OrnAhVvShUIHX-gCAkQ6AEwAnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22central%20school%20of%20dance%20music%22&f=false Chiltern, John. ''Who's Who in British Jazz'', 2nd Edition (2004) p 232]</ref> By then its address was 195 [[Wardour Street]] in [[Soho]] (original building has been demolished).<ref>[https://www.nationaljazzarchive.org.uk/explore/journals/jazz-news/volume5-no44/1276050-jazz-news-volume5-no44-0010?q=ottilie%20patterson ''Jazz News'' vol 5 no 44, 1 November 1961, p 18]</ref> Among the teaching staff at the school were [[Johnny Dankworth]], [[Jack Brymer]], [[Kenny Baker (trumpeter)|Kenny Baker]], [[Bert Weedon]] and [[Ike Isaacs (guitarist)|Ike Isaacs]], as well as Gilder himself.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-ivor-mairants-1147017.html Obituary, 'Ivor Mairants' in ''The Independent'', 26 February 1998]</ref>\n\nGilder is remembered with gratitude by the poet and musician [[Labi Siffre]] in his poem \"education education education\".<ref>[https://www.intothelight.info/ozz/poems__poetry__political/index.html ''Into the light'' (Labi Siffri website)]</ref> Siffre studied at the Gilder school, as did [[Richard Wright (musician)|Richard Wright]] of [[Pink Floyd]], [[Junior Campbell]], [[John Chilton]] and (as a part time student in the spring of 1963) the 15 year-old [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]].<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Unmasked-Andrew-Lloyd-Webber/dp/000823759X/ref=sr_1_2?keywords=andrew+lloyd+webber&qid=1582621552&s=books&sr=1-2 Lloyd Webber, Andrew. ''Unmasked: A Biography'' (2018), p 41-42]</ref> The school attracted notable expatriate musicians from Africa and the Caribbean including [[Ebo Taylor]], (the [[Ghana|Ghanaian]] [[Afrobeat|afrobeat]] guitarist, composer and bandleader), [[Mulatu Astatke]] (considered the father of [[Music of Ethiopia|Ethio-jazz]]) and [[Teddy Osei]] (founder member of [[Osibisa]], a band that played a central role in developing a more international awareness of African music in the 1970s).\n\nAs a conductor Gilder was an active choral director and arranger. In April 1951 he was appointed Musical Director of the 50-strong Ilford Girls' Choir and secured some high profile bookings for them, including a live broadcast of [[Variety Bandbox]] on the [[BBC Light Programme]], accompanying the young [[Julie Andrews]]. However, something went wrong and he resigned from the post in April 1952.<ref>[http://www.overthefootlights.co.uk/Entertaining%20Ilford%20v3.pub.pdf Entertaining Ilford]</ref> He also arranged choral parts for [[Geraldo (bandleader)|Geraldo and his Orchestra]] (as chorus master of \"the Geraldo Glee Club\")<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/51f24d1bd62c41628e4743fc0727ad1e ''Radio Times'', issue 1692, 15 April 1956]956, p 37</ref> and appeared at the [[Royal Festival Hall]] in London as a conductor and pianist. Gilder also wrote plays, poetry and fiction and contributed to music periodicals.<ref name=gilder/>\n\nHe was married (on 23 December 1939) with two daughters, and lived in his later years at 21 Fieldend, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VXMmAQAAIAAJ&dq=editions%3AWIiRzRg04PMC&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Eric+Gilder Twickenham]. <ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VXMmAQAAIAAJ&dq=editions%3AWIiRzRg04PMC&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Eric+Gilder ''International Who's Who in Music'', 1992]</ref>\n\n===Composer===\nAs a composer Gilder has been entirely forgotten, but he wrote orchestral, choral, theatre and television music, [[pantomime]] music and lyrics, collaborating with the actor and writer John Crocker (1925-2015), as well as 200 songs (some with [[Salon music|salon orchestra]] parts) and numerous solo piano pieces.<ref name=gilder/>\n\n===Selected Works===\n*''Seascape'' for piano and orchestra (1939)\n*''The Tide'' for soprano, baritone, chorus, organ and orchestra (1945)\n*''Christmas Sounds'' for soli, chorus and orchestra (1950)\n* ''A Busy Song'': three part song for soprano, mezzo and alto with piano (words and music by Gilder) (published Curwen, 1951)\n* ''Gavotte'' for piano (published Noel Gay Music, 1951)\n* ''Hear Our Music'', choir and piano (published Manor Music Co, 1951)\n* ''I Will Wait'', song (words and music by Gilder) (published Manor Music Co, 1951)\n*''Nursery Suite'' for orchestra (1953)\n*''A Sea Suite'' for orchestra (1954)\n* ''La Contadina'' (The Little Match Girl), soli and light orchestra (published Ricordi, 1954)\n* ''Three Gifts'', soli and light orchestra (words and music by Gilder) (published, Ricordi, 1954)\n*''A Processional Overture'' (1975)\n*Sonata for Violin and Piano (1979)\n*''Three Pastorals'' for orchestra (1981)\n* ''Danse Fantastique'', piano duet\n* Many pantomime scores and lyrics in collaboration with John Crocker, including ''Aladdin, Puss in Boots'' and ''Red Riding Hood'' (1960s)\n\n===Author===\n* ''Troubled Waters'' (radio play, broadcast 17 July 1946, BBC Home Service)<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/217934fd62354d669b00a027b5edbfcd ''Radio Times'' issue 1189, 14 July 1946, p 12]</ref>\n* ''Mister Potter's Play'' (radio play, broadcast 15 May 1948, BBC Home Service)<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/6cc82607d1844c2eb60fb899c6d3d2d2 ''Radio Times'' issue 1282, 9 May 1948, p 20]</ref>\n* ''Dictionary of Composers and Their Music'' (with June G Port, 1978)\n* ''The Back Stairs'', short story (broadcast 18 June 1980)<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/6ac4f657cea54fa7bd560f5f31c7fb47 ''Radio Times'' issue 2953, 12 June 1980, p 53]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilder, Eric}}\n[[Category:English musicologists]]\n[[Category:English composers]]\n[[Category:English conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:British male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:English classical pianists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century musicologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:British music educators]]\n[[Category: Music schools in England]]\n", "text_old": "'''Eric Gilder''' (25 December 1911 \u2013 1 June 2000) was an [[England|English]] [[musicology|musicologist]], and also a [[teacher]], [[Conducting|conductor]], [[composer]] and [[pianist]]. He was best known as the principal of the Eric Gilder School of Music.\n\n==Biography==\nGilder was a pupil at [[Henry Thornton Grammar School|Henry Thornton School]] in Clapham from 1926 until 1931, and composed the original school song.<ref>[http://www.oldthorntoniansclapham.org.uk/page8.htm Old Thorntonians Association]</ref> He initially studied mathematics and physics, but in 1936 he gained a scholarship to the [[Royal College of Music]] where he studied under [[John Ireland (composer)|John Ireland]], [[Ralph Vaughan Williams]], [[Constant Lambert]] and Sir [[Malcolm Sargent]]. He continued there until interrupted by war service.<ref name=gilder>[http://www.musicweb-international.com/Classpedia/Gilder.htm The 'Eric Gilder' entry from his own ''Dictionary of Composers and Their Music'' (1985)]</ref>\n\nAfter the war he worked variously as a pianist, conductor and broadcaster, and as principal of his own school of music. He began his career as a teacher at the Central School of Dance Music at 15 [[West Street, London|West Street]] in London. This was originally established in 1950 by jazz guitarist [[Ivor Mairants]], primarily for jazz, big band and popular music players. Mairants handed the school over to Gilder in 1960 and it became the Eric Gilder School of Music.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=DGuvAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA232&lpg=PA232&dq=%22central+school+of+dance+music%22&source=bl&ots=0sn4VQxKtf&sig=ACfU3U1A4Iju8xPSIejucoiNs1pfsFVOfQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjzwey1-OrnAhVvShUIHX-gCAkQ6AEwAnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22central%20school%20of%20dance%20music%22&f=false Chiltern, John. ''Who's Who in British Jazz'', 2nd Edition (2004) p 232]</ref> By then its address was 195 [[Wardour Street]] in [[Soho]] (original building has been demolished).<ref>[https://www.nationaljazzarchive.org.uk/explore/journals/jazz-news/volume5-no44/1276050-jazz-news-volume5-no44-0010?q=ottilie%20patterson ''Jazz News'' vol 5 no 44, 1 November 1961, p 18]</ref> Among the teaching staff at the school were [[Johnny Dankworth]], [[Jack Brymer]], [[Kenny Baker (trumpeter)|Kenny Baker]], [[Bert Weedon]] and [[Ike Isaacs (guitarist)|Ike Isaacs]], as well as Gilder himself.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-ivor-mairants-1147017.html Obituary, 'Ivor Mairants' in ''The Independent'', 26 February 1998]</ref>\n\nGilder is remembered with gratitude by the poet and musician [[Labi Siffre]] in his poem \"education education education\".<ref>[https://www.intothelight.info/ozz/poems__poetry__political/index.html ''Into the light'' (Labi Siffri website)]</ref> Siffre studied at the Gilder school, as did [[Richard Wright (musician)|Richard Wright]] of [[Pink Floyd]], [[Junior Campbell]], [[John Chilton]] and (as a part time student in the spring of 1963) the 15 year-old [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]].<ref>[https://www.amazon.co.uk/Unmasked-Andrew-Lloyd-Webber/dp/000823759X/ref=sr_1_2?keywords=andrew+lloyd+webber&qid=1582621552&s=books&sr=1-2 Lloyd Webber, Andrew. ''Unmasked: A Biography'' (2018), p 41-42]</ref> The school attracted notable expatriate musicians from Africa and the Caribbean including [[Ebo Taylor]], (the [[Ghana|Ghanaian]] [[Afrobeat|afrobeat]] guitarist, composer and bandleader), [[Mulatu Astatke]] (considered the father of [[Music of Ethiopia|Ethio-jazz]]) and [[Teddy Osei]] (founder member of [[Osibisa]], a band that played a central role in developing a more international awareness of African music in the 1970s).\n\nAs a conductor Gilder was an active choral director and arranger. In April 1951 he was appointed Musical Director of the 50-strong Ilford Girls' Choir and secured some high profile bookings for them, including a live broadcast of [[Variety Bandbox]] on the [[BBC Light Programme]], accompanying the young [[Julie Andrews]]. However, something went wrong and he resigned from the post in April 1952.<ref>[http://www.overthefootlights.co.uk/Entertaining%20Ilford%20v3.pub.pdf Entertaining Ilford]</ref> He also arranged choral parts for [[Geraldo (bandleader)|Geraldo and his Orchestra]] (as chorus master of \"the Geraldo Glee Club\")<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/51f24d1bd62c41628e4743fc0727ad1e ''Radio Times'', issue 1692, 15 April 1956]956, p 37</ref> and appeared at the [[Royal Festival Hall]] in London as a conductor and pianist. Gilder also wrote plays, poetry and fiction and contributed to music periodicals.<ref name=gilder/>\n\nHe was married (on 23 December 1939) with two daughters, and lived at 21 Fieldend, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VXMmAQAAIAAJ&dq=editions%3AWIiRzRg04PMC&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Eric+Gilder Twickenham]. <ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VXMmAQAAIAAJ&dq=editions%3AWIiRzRg04PMC&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Eric+Gilder ''International Who's Who in Music'', 1992]</ref>\n\n===Composer===\nAs a composer Gilder has been entirely forgotten, but he wrote orchestral, choral, theatre and television music, [[pantomime]] music and lyrics, collaborating with the actor and writer John Crocker (1925-2015), as well as 200 songs (some with [[Salon music|salon orchestra]] parts) and numerous solo piano pieces.<ref name=gilder/>\n\n===Selected Works===\n*''Seascape'' for piano and orchestra (1939)\n*''The Tide'' for soprano, baritone, chorus, organ and orchestra (1945)\n*''Christmas Sounds'' for soli, chorus and orchestra (1950)\n* ''A Busy Song'': three part song for soprano, mezzo and alto with piano (words and music by Gilder) (published Curwen, 1951)\n* ''Gavotte'' for piano (published Noel Gay Music, 1951)\n* ''Hear Our Music'', choir and piano (published Manor Music Co, 1951)\n* ''I Will Wait'', song (words and music by Gilder) (published Manor Music Co, 1951)\n*''Nursery Suite'' for orchestra (1953)\n*''A Sea Suite'' for orchestra (1954)\n* ''La Contadina'' (The Little Match Girl), soli and light orchestra (published Ricordi, 1954)\n* ''Three Gifts'', soli and light orchestra (words and music by Gilder) (published, Ricordi, 1954)\n*''A Processional Overture'' (1975)\n*Sonata for Violin and Piano (1979)\n*''Three Pastorals'' for orchestra (1981)\n* ''Danse Fantastique'', piano duet\n* Many pantomime scores and lyrics in collaboration with John Crocker, including ''Aladdin, Puss in Boots'' and ''Red Riding Hood'' (1960s)\n\n===Author===\n* ''Troubled Waters'' (radio play, broadcast 17 July 1946, BBC Home Service)<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/217934fd62354d669b00a027b5edbfcd ''Radio Times'' issue 1189, 14 July 1946, p 12]</ref>\n* ''Mister Potter's Play'' (radio play, broadcast 15 May 1948, BBC Home Service)<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/page/6cc82607d1844c2eb60fb899c6d3d2d2 ''Radio Times'' issue 1282, 9 May 1948, p 20]</ref>\n* ''Dictionary of Composers and Their Music'' (with June G Port, 1978)\n* ''The Back Stairs'', short story (broadcast 18 June 1980)<ref>[https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/6ac4f657cea54fa7bd560f5f31c7fb47 ''Radio Times'' issue 2953, 12 June 1980, p 53]</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilder, Eric}}\n[[Category:English musicologists]]\n[[Category:English composers]]\n[[Category:English conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:British male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:English classical pianists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal College of Music]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:20th-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:20th-century classical pianists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English musicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century musicologists]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male musicians]]\n[[Category:British music educators]]\n[[Category: Music schools in England]]\n", "name_user": "Sfjohna", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Gilder"}
{"title_page": "Arjun Mark", "text_new": "= Arjun Mark =\n'''Arjun Mark''' (born 1980) is an acclaimed Indian [[Fashion photography|fashion photographer]] regarded for his bold and modern aesthetic. Arjun\u2019s photography style in ''Fashion'' and ''Beauty'' had made him one of the celebrated photographers in India.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialketchup.in/photographers-of-the-decade/|title=11 Photographers of the decade who captured our hearts|last=Parmar|first=Priyanka|date=2019-12-12|website=Social Ketchup|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nHe is recognised for being listed on '''[[L\u00fcrzer's Archive|L\u00fcrzer's Archive's]]''' 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide 2020/21<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.luerzersarchive.com/en/magazine/print-detail/arjun-mark-70877.html|title=Arjun Mark|website=Luerzer's Archive - Advertising worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> and is a Canon EOS Ambassador for India.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamflame.net/photography/top-8-fashion-photographers-of-india-in-2018/|title=Top 8 Fashion Photographers Of India In 2018 {{!}} GlamFlame|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.schoolofphotography.co.in/best-fashion-photographers-last-one-decade/|title=Best fashion photographers in the last one decade|last=|first=|date=|website=School of photography|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nArjun\u2019s work was curated at exhibitions in New York during the [[Lucie Awards|LUCIE AWARDS]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.luciefoundation.org/2017-lucie-week-events-announced-oct-25-29/|title=2017 Lucie Week Events Announced, Oct. 25-29|date=2017-10-20|website=Lucie Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> He has won the prestigious '''''[[Px3|PX3]]''' Awards, Paris'' in 2018<ref name=\":12\" /> and the Black and White [https://www.thespiderawards.com/ Spider Awards] amongst many others. Arjun's photographs have been published in internationally acclaimed publication such as [[Communication Arts (magazine)|Communication Arts]] and [https://photopaper.world/about/ Photo Paper] magazine in Germany.\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Arjun Mark\n| image              = Arjun Mark Photographer.jpg\n| caption            = Arjun Mark at his studio in 2018\n| birth_date         = 1980\n| birth_place        = South India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Fashion Photographer\n| website            = http://www.arjunmark.com\n}}\n\n== Early life and background ==\nArjun Mark was born in the southernmost part of India and grew up moving across towns and cities within [[South India]]. His mother was an artist and hence it is from her where Arjun acquired a flair for art.\n\nAfter schooling, he enrolled for a Bachelor\u2019s degree in Computer Science which he discontinued shortly to peruse a three-year Bachelor\u2019s degree in [[Visual communication|Visual Communication]] at [[Loyola College, Chennai|Loyola College]], [[Chennai]]. This is where he got introduced to photography for the first time. Since then, there was no looking back from photography as this medium of art made him recognise another altogether unexpected side of him that had become his approach of artistic exploration.\n\nDuring college Arjun was very interested in scientific [[high-speed photography]]. His inspiration was [[Harold Eugene Edgerton]]. He experimented capturing water splash and speeding air-gun pellets in his room with [[Do it yourself|DIY]] sound triggers and [[Motion detector|motion detectors]]. All of these experiments were done with conventional film [[Digital single-lens reflex camera|DSLR]] cameras. To fund his film rolls and equipment during college, he worked as a part-time freelance photographer shooting fashion shows and events.\n\n== Early Career ==\nArjun used to apprentice photographers part-time during college. After completing his degree in B.Sc [[Visual communication|Visual Communication]] at [[Loyola College, Chennai|Loyola college]] in 2004, he was a full-time apprentice with a photographer in Chennai for two years before branching out independently in 2007. Arjun worked independently on assignments in Chennai until 2009.\n\nEarly 2009, Arjun received an opportunity to apprentice under a reputed fashion photographer based in [[Mumbai]]. He moved to Mumbai where he apprenticed for two years and independently branched out in Mumbai in 2011.\n\n== Recent Career ==\nOver the years, Arjun\u2019s photography style had evolved and progressed of find his niche in Fashion and Beauty, that had made him one of the highly celebrated photographers in India. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialketchup.in/photographers-of-the-decade/|title=Photographers of the decade who captured our hearts|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nArjun has worked with leading international editorial publications such as [[GQ]], [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]], [[Elle (magazine)|ELLE]], various fashion labels, [[Bollywood]] celebrities and sports personalities. <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://fashionphotographersmumbai.com/blog/2017/12/12/top-10-fashion-photographers-of-india/|title=Top 10 Fashion Photographers of India|last=admin|date=2017-12-12|website=Fashion Photography Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nHis current gamut of work includes well recognised campaigns for Indian and International cosmetic brands such as [[Est\u00e9e Lauder Companies|Estee Lauder]], [[Clinique]], [[Nivea]], [[Lakm\u00e9 Cosmetics|Lakme]]\u00b4, [[Vaseline]] and [[Pond's|Ponds]].\n\nArjun is listed in the [[L\u00fcrzer's Archive|L\u00fcrzer\u2019s Archive]] 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide 2020/21, which is the world\u2019s leading publication for outstanding advertising.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/2013/12/prweb11393219.htm|title=200 Best Ad Photographers \u2013 L\u00fcrzer\u2019s Archive Showcases Recent Work Shot By The World\u2019s Best Ad Photographers|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOne of his most distinguished assignments in 2014 was to photograph [[Jeff Bezos]] for the cover page of [[GQ (Indian edition)|GQ]] magazine.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Awards and Acclaim ==\n\n=== 2020 ===\nArjun was listed in '''L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume 2020/21'''<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arjunmark.com/awards-acclaim/|title=Awards & Acclaim \u2013 ARJUN MARK|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>[http://arjunmark.com/awards-acclaim/] for the third time. [[L\u00fcrzer's Archive]] is the world\u2019s leading publication for outstanding advertising in the industry.<ref name=\":8\" />\n[[File:ArjunMark_Lurzers-Archive-200BEST.jpg|thumb|Listed in L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume  2020/21.]]\n\n=== 2018 ===\nThe prestigious '''''PX3, PARIS''''' ''([[Px3|Prix de la Photographie]])'' honoured Arjun with a '''''SILVER''''' for his fashion story ''\"Fetish Fashion\".''<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://px3.fr/winners/px3/2018/|title=Single Winner|website=PX3 Photography Awards|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> His winning pictures were displayed at the [https://www.espacebeaurepaire.com/ Espace Beaurepaire], France in July 2018.\n[[File:PX3-certificate-silver.pdf|thumb|Certificate Of Achievement, from '''PX3''' Paris for Arjun's achievement in the 2018 Photography Awards.]]\nFor the second time, Arjun had been listed once again in '''L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE'S 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume 2018/19,'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.luerzersarchive.com/en/magazine/print-detail/arjun-mark-66270.html|title=Arjun Mark|website=Luerzer's Archive - Advertising worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> chosen for one of his self-commissioned assignments featuring a beauty feature with nuns.[[File:ArjunMark_LURZER'S_ARCHIVE_200_Best_Ad_Photographers_Worldwide.jpg|thumb|Published in L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume 2018/19]]\nHe had also received '''''1 Honourable Mention''''' in ''<nowiki/>'Beauty'<nowiki/>'', and '''''1 Honourable Menti''on''' in the ''<nowiki/>'Nude'<nowiki/>'' category this year at the '''[[International Photography Awards|IPA 2018]]'''.\n\n=== 2017 ===\nArjun\u2019s work was curated at the '''''\u2018BEST OF SHOW\u2019''''' exhibition in New York during the [[Lucie Awards|'''LUCIE AWARDS''']] Week at [[Zankel Hall]]<ref name=\":4\" />, a coveted collective attended by [[Peter Lindbergh]] and other artists of eminence<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.magazzinifotografici.it/ipa-international-photography-award-best-of-show-2017/|title=IPA \u2013 International Photography Award \u2013 BEST of SHOW 2017 {{!}} Magazzini Fotografici|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=International Photography Awards 2017|publisher=IPA|year=2017|isbn=|location=CA 90004, USA|pages=pages 2 and 4}}</ref>. \n[[File:Curated_at_the_\u2018BEST_OF_SHOW\u2019_exhibition_in_New_York,_that_had_won_1st_place_at_the_IPA(Lucie_Awards).jpg|thumb|Curated at the \u2018BEST OF SHOW\u2019 exhibition in New York, that had won 1st place at the IPA(Lucie Awards).]]\nArjun received '''''1ST PLACE''''' at the '''(IPA)''' '''LUCIE AWARDS''' in the category, 'Advertising and Beauty', from the series \"WATERCOLOUR\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=IPA *17|first=|date=2017|title=IPA *17|url=https://photoawards.com/books/ipa17.pdf|journal=PhotoAwards.com|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.photoawards.com/winner/zoom.php?eid=8-143136-17|title=IPA 2017 Winner / WaterColour / Arjun Mark / Arjun Mark|website=www.photoawards.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nBesides the above mentioned, one of Arjun's pictures received a '''Honourable Mention''' in the ''<nowiki/>'Nude''' category. \n\n=== 2014 ===\nArjun won '''''2ND PLACE'',''' and was honoured with a '''''<nowiki/>'Merit Of Excellence\"''''' in the category ''<nowiki/>'Fashion'<nowiki/>'' at the '''9th ANNUAL''' '''[https://www.thespiderawards.com/ BLACK AND WHITE SPIDER AWARDS].''' Spider Awards celebrates photographers who operate at the highest levels of their craft and is the leading international award honouring excellence in black and white photography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thespiderawards.com/resources-winners-press.php|title=Press Release - The Spider Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [https://www.thespiderawards.com/resources-winners-press.php (Press release)]\n\nOther achievements this year include '''''1 Honourable Mention''''' and '''''6 Nominations''''' in ''Fashion and Beauty'' category at the Spider Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thespiderawards.com/gallery/9th/search?t=arjun+mark&o=a&Submit=Search|title=9th Winners Gallery {{!}} Spider Awards|website=www.thespiderawards.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 ===\nArjun was one of the jury on the panel of the Black & White [https://www.thegalaawards.com/ WPGA Awards].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://gerger.com/about/awards/581398/::/24528::/40584|title=Ger Ger - B&W Photographer of the Year Nominee, WPGA, UK|website=gerger.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nHis work was chosen to be showcased at the 9th year of KAPA([https://www.heinzbaumann.com/photoblog/?p=1108 The Korea Advertising Photographers Association]) International Advertising Photography Exhibition held in Seoul.\n\n=== 2012 ===\nArjun's advertising campaign for a luxury fine jewellery brand '[https://www.farahkhanworld.com/ Farah Khan]', was listed in '''L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume 2012/13.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.luerzersarchive.com/en/magazine/print-detail/farah-khan-fine-jewellery-49742.html|title=Farah Khan Fine Jewellery|website=Luerzer's Archive - Advertising worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> L\u00fcrzer's Archive 200 BEST is the world\u2019s leading publication for outstanding advertising photography in the industry.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== 2011 ===\nIn March 2011, Arjun Mark was credited with the prestigious '''''\u201cAward of Excellence\u201d''''' title at the '''COMMUNICATION ARTS''' in the Advertising category'''.''' His winning project '[http://www.farahkhanworld.com Farah Khan Fine Jewellery'] has been published in the internationally acclaimed publication '''\"Communication Arts, Photography Annual 2011\u201d.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commarts.com/project/18984/farah-khan-fine-jewellery|title=Farah Khan Fine Jewellery|website=Communication Arts|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nArjun was one of the jury on the panel of the Black & White [https://www.thegalaawards.com/ WPGA Awards]<ref name=\":9\" />, with the likes of [http://www.davidzimmerman.com/ David Zimmerman]. \n\nHis work had been published in The [https://photopaper.world/about/ PHOTO PAPER] magazine, Germany.\n\nHe also received '''''2 Nominations''''' at the International Photography Master\u2019s Cup and '''''1 Nomination''''' at the Black and White Spider Awards.\n\n=== 2010 ===\nArjun received an '''''\u201cAward of Excellence\u201d''''' in the portrait category for a self-commissioned project on South Indian Tribes. His work was published in the internationally acclaimed publication '''\"Communication Arts, Best of Photography Annual 2010\".''' \n\nAt the [https://www.thegalaawards.com/ WPGA](Worldwide Photography Gala Awards), Arjun was the '''''WINNER''''' and his work received the '''''BEST OF SHOW''''' ''title as-well'''''.''' \n\nArjun received '''''2 Honourable Mentions''''' at the '''[https://px3.fr/ PX3 Paris],''' a total of '''''9 Honourable Mentions''''' at the '''IPA([https://www.colorawards.com/ International Color Awards])''', and '''''2 Nominations''''' at the '''International Photography Master\u2019s Cup'''.\n\n== Personal Life ==\nArjun is an avid [[Sport Fishing|sport-fishing]] enthusiast<ref name=\":10\" />, and an ardent [[Ocean life]] and [[Wildlife]] lover. \n\n== External Links ==\n[http://www.arjunmark.com Official website] of Arjun Mark \n\n[https://www.femina.in/fashion/fashion-news/four-established-professionals-share-their-success-mantras-129354-1.html Femina July 2019 Issue] - Four established professional share their success mantras\n\n[https://www.thepeacockmagazine.com/photographer-in-focus-arjun-mark/ Peacock Magazine Interview] - PHOTOGRAPHER IN FOCUS: ARJUN MARK\n\n[https://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/world-photography-day-top-indian-photographers-share-their-iconic-pics/story-fjkVDxUVUr7UNcbWkV5YGM.html HindustanTimes News Article] - Top Indian photographers on World Photography Day\n\n[https://www.glamflame.net/photography/top-8-fashion-photographers-of-india-in-2018/ Online Blog] - Top 8 Fashion Photographers Of India In 2018\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "text_old": "= Arjun Mark =\n'''Arjun Mark''' (born 1980) is an acclaimed Indian [[Fashion photography|fashion photographer]] regarded for his bold and modern aesthetic. Arjun\u2019s photography style in ''Fashion'' and ''Beauty'' had made him one of the celebrated photographers in India.<ref name=\":11\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialketchup.in/photographers-of-the-decade/|title=11 Photographers of the decade who captured our hearts|last=Parmar|first=Priyanka|date=2019-12-12|website=Social Ketchup|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nHe is recognised for being listed on '''[[L\u00fcrzer's Archive|L\u00fcrzer's Archive's]]''' 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide 2020/21<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.luerzersarchive.com/en/magazine/print-detail/arjun-mark-70877.html|title=Arjun Mark|website=Luerzer's Archive - Advertising worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> and is a Canon EOS Ambassador for India.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.glamflame.net/photography/top-8-fashion-photographers-of-india-in-2018/|title=Top 8 Fashion Photographers Of India In 2018 {{!}} GlamFlame|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":11\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.schoolofphotography.co.in/best-fashion-photographers-last-one-decade/|title=Best fashion photographers in the last one decade|last=|first=|date=|website=School of photography|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nArjun\u2019s work was curated at exhibitions in New York during the [[Lucie Awards|LUCIE AWARDS]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.luciefoundation.org/2017-lucie-week-events-announced-oct-25-29/|title=2017 Lucie Week Events Announced, Oct. 25-29|date=2017-10-20|website=Lucie Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> He has won the prestigious '''''[[Px3|PX3]]''' Awards, Paris'' in 2018<ref name=\":12\" /> and the Black and White [https://www.thespiderawards.com/ Spider Awards] amongst many others. Arjun's photographs have been published in internationally acclaimed publication such as [[Communication Arts (magazine)|Communication Arts]] and [https://photopaper.world/about/ Photo Paper] magazine in Germany.\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Arjun Mark\n| image              = Arjun Mark Photographer.jpg\n| caption            = Arjun Mark at his studio in 2018\n| birth_date         = 1980\n| birth_place        = South India\n| nationality        = Indian\n| occupation         = Fashion Photographer\n| website            = http://www.arjunmark.com\n}}\n\n== Early life and background ==\nArjun Mark was born in the southernmost part of India and grew up moving across towns and cities within [[South India]]. His mother was an artist and hence it is from her where Arjun acquired a flair for art.\n\nAfter schooling, he enrolled for a Bachelor\u2019s degree in Computer Science which he discontinued shortly to peruse a three-year Bachelor\u2019s degree in [[Visual communication|Visual Communication]] at [[Loyola College, Chennai|Loyola College]], [[Chennai]]. This is where he got introduced to photography for the first time. Since then, there was no looking back from photography as this medium of art made him recognise another altogether unexpected side of him that had become his approach of artistic exploration.\n\nDuring college Arjun was very interested in scientific [[high-speed photography]]. His inspiration was [[Harold Eugene Edgerton]]. He experimented capturing water splash and speeding air-gun pellets in his room with [[Do it yourself|DIY]] sound triggers and [[Motion detector|motion detectors]]. All of these experiments were done with conventional film [[Digital single-lens reflex camera|DSLR]] cameras. To fund his film rolls and equipment during college, he worked as a part-time freelance photographer shooting fashion shows and events.\n\n== Early Career ==\nArjun used to apprentice photographers part-time during college. After completing his degree in B.Sc [[Visual communication|Visual Communication]] at [[Loyola College, Chennai|Loyola college]] in 2004, he was a full-time apprentice with a photographer in Chennai. He had worked with him for two years before branching out independently in 2007. Later, Arjun worked independently on assignments in Chennai for almost two years. He was at the same time, looking out to move to a larger market in a larger city.\n\nIn 2009, Arjun received an opportunity to apprentice under a reputed fashion photographer based in [[Mumbai]]. He moved to Mumbai where he apprenticed for two years. Later, Arjun independently branched out in Mumbai by 2011.\n\n== Recent Career ==\nOver the years, Arjun\u2019s photography style had evolved and progressed of find his niche in Fashion and Beauty, that had made him one of the highly celebrated photographers in India. <ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.socialketchup.in/photographers-of-the-decade/|title=Photographers of the decade who captured our hearts|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nArjun has worked with leading international editorial publications such as [[GQ]], [[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]], [[Elle (magazine)|ELLE]], various fashion labels, [[Bollywood]] celebrities and sports personalities. <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://fashionphotographersmumbai.com/blog/2017/12/12/top-10-fashion-photographers-of-india/|title=Top 10 Fashion Photographers of India|last=admin|date=2017-12-12|website=Fashion Photography Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nHis current gamut of work includes well recognised campaigns for Indian and International cosmetic brands such as [[Est\u00e9e Lauder Companies|Estee Lauder]], [[Clinique]], [[Nivea]], [[Lakm\u00e9 Cosmetics|Lakme]]\u00b4, [[Vaseline]] and [[Pond's|Ponds]].\n\nArjun is listed in the [[L\u00fcrzer's Archive|L\u00fcrzer\u2019s Archive]] 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide 2020/21, which is the world\u2019s leading publication for outstanding advertising.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.prweb.com/releases/2013/12/prweb11393219.htm|title=200 Best Ad Photographers \u2013 L\u00fcrzer\u2019s Archive Showcases Recent Work Shot By The World\u2019s Best Ad Photographers|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOne of his most distinguished assignments in 2014 was to photograph [[Jeff Bezos]] for the cover page of [[GQ (Indian edition)|GQ]] magazine.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Awards and Acclaim ==\n\n=== 2020 ===\nArjun was listed in '''L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume 2020/21'''<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://arjunmark.com/awards-acclaim/|title=Awards & Acclaim \u2013 ARJUN MARK|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>[http://arjunmark.com/awards-acclaim/] for the third time. [[L\u00fcrzer's Archive]] is the world\u2019s leading publication for outstanding advertising in the industry.<ref name=\":8\" />\n[[File:ArjunMark_Lurzers-Archive-200BEST.jpg|thumb|Listed in L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume  2020/21.]]\n\n=== 2018 ===\nThe prestigious '''''PX3, PARIS''''' ''([[Px3|Prix de la Photographie]])'' honoured Arjun with a '''''SILVER''''' for his fashion story ''\"Fetish Fashion\".''<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=http://px3.fr/winners/px3/2018/|title=Single Winner|website=PX3 Photography Awards|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> His winning pictures were displayed at the [https://www.espacebeaurepaire.com/ Espace Beaurepaire], France in July 2018.\n[[File:PX3-certificate-silver.pdf|thumb|Certificate Of Achievement, from '''PX3''' Paris for Arjun's achievement in the 2018 Photography Awards.]]\nFor the second time, Arjun had been listed once again in '''L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE'S 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume 2018/19,'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.luerzersarchive.com/en/magazine/print-detail/arjun-mark-66270.html|title=Arjun Mark|website=Luerzer's Archive - Advertising worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> chosen for one of his self-commissioned assignments featuring a beauty feature with nuns.[[File:ArjunMark_LURZER'S_ARCHIVE_200_Best_Ad_Photographers_Worldwide.jpg|thumb|Published in L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume 2018/19]]\nHe had also received '''''1 Honourable Mention''''' in ''<nowiki/>'Beauty'<nowiki/>'', and '''''1 Honourable Menti''on''' in the ''<nowiki/>'Nude'<nowiki/>'' category this year at the '''[[International Photography Awards|IPA 2018]]'''.\n\n=== 2017 ===\nArjun\u2019s work was curated at the '''''\u2018BEST OF SHOW\u2019''''' exhibition in New York during the [[Lucie Awards|'''LUCIE AWARDS''']] Week at [[Zankel Hall]]<ref name=\":4\" />, a coveted collective attended by [[Peter Lindbergh]] and other artists of eminence<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.magazzinifotografici.it/ipa-international-photography-award-best-of-show-2017/|title=IPA \u2013 International Photography Award \u2013 BEST of SHOW 2017 {{!}} Magazzini Fotografici|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=International Photography Awards 2017|publisher=IPA|year=2017|isbn=|location=CA 90004, USA|pages=pages 2 and 4}}</ref>. \n[[File:Curated_at_the_\u2018BEST_OF_SHOW\u2019_exhibition_in_New_York,_that_had_won_1st_place_at_the_IPA(Lucie_Awards).jpg|thumb|Curated at the \u2018BEST OF SHOW\u2019 exhibition in New York, that had won 1st place at the IPA(Lucie Awards).]]\nArjun received '''''1ST PLACE''''' at the '''(IPA)''' '''LUCIE AWARDS''' in the category, 'Advertising and Beauty', from the series \"WATERCOLOUR\".<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=IPA *17|first=|date=2017|title=IPA *17|url=https://photoawards.com/books/ipa17.pdf|journal=PhotoAwards.com|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.photoawards.com/winner/zoom.php?eid=8-143136-17|title=IPA 2017 Winner / WaterColour / Arjun Mark / Arjun Mark|website=www.photoawards.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nBesides the above mentioned, one of Arjun's pictures received a '''Honourable Mention''' in the ''<nowiki/>'Nude''' category. \n\n=== 2014 ===\nArjun won '''''2ND PLACE'',''' and was honoured with a '''''<nowiki/>'Merit Of Excellence\"''''' in the category ''<nowiki/>'Fashion'<nowiki/>'' at the '''9th ANNUAL''' '''[https://www.thespiderawards.com/ BLACK AND WHITE SPIDER AWARDS].''' Spider Awards celebrates photographers who operate at the highest levels of their craft and is the leading international award honouring excellence in black and white photography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thespiderawards.com/resources-winners-press.php|title=Press Release - The Spider Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> [https://www.thespiderawards.com/resources-winners-press.php (Press release)]\n\nOther achievements this year include '''''1 Honourable Mention''''' and '''''6 Nominations''''' in ''Fashion and Beauty'' category at the Spider Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thespiderawards.com/gallery/9th/search?t=arjun+mark&o=a&Submit=Search|title=9th Winners Gallery {{!}} Spider Awards|website=www.thespiderawards.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013 ===\nArjun was one of the jury on the panel of the Black & White [https://www.thegalaawards.com/ WPGA Awards].<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://gerger.com/about/awards/581398/::/24528::/40584|title=Ger Ger - B&W Photographer of the Year Nominee, WPGA, UK|website=gerger.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nHis work was chosen to be showcased at the 9th year of KAPA([https://www.heinzbaumann.com/photoblog/?p=1108 The Korea Advertising Photographers Association]) International Advertising Photography Exhibition held in Seoul.\n\n=== 2012 ===\nArjun's advertising campaign for a luxury fine jewellery brand '[https://www.farahkhanworld.com/ Farah Khan]', was listed in '''L\u00dcRZER'S ARCHIVE 200 Best Ad Photographers Worldwide, Volume 2012/13.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.luerzersarchive.com/en/magazine/print-detail/farah-khan-fine-jewellery-49742.html|title=Farah Khan Fine Jewellery|website=Luerzer's Archive - Advertising worldwide|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> L\u00fcrzer's Archive 200 BEST is the world\u2019s leading publication for outstanding advertising photography in the industry.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n=== 2011 ===\nIn March 2011, Arjun Mark was credited with the prestigious '''''\u201cAward of Excellence\u201d''''' title at the '''COMMUNICATION ARTS''' in the Advertising category'''.''' His winning project '[http://www.farahkhanworld.com Farah Khan Fine Jewellery'] has been published in the internationally acclaimed publication '''\"Communication Arts, Photography Annual 2011\u201d.'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commarts.com/project/18984/farah-khan-fine-jewellery|title=Farah Khan Fine Jewellery|website=Communication Arts|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nArjun was one of the jury on the panel of the Black & White [https://www.thegalaawards.com/ WPGA Awards]<ref name=\":9\" />, with the likes of [http://www.davidzimmerman.com/ David Zimmerman]. \n\nHis work had been published in The [https://photopaper.world/about/ PHOTO PAPER] magazine, Germany.\n\nHe also received '''''2 Nominations''''' at the International Photography Master\u2019s Cup and '''''1 Nomination''''' at the Black and White Spider Awards.\n\n=== 2010 ===\nArjun received an '''''\u201cAward of Excellence\u201d''''' in the portrait category for a self-commissioned project on South Indian Tribes. His work was published in the internationally acclaimed publication '''\"Communication Arts, Best of Photography Annual 2010\".''' \n\nAt the [https://www.thegalaawards.com/ WPGA](Worldwide Photography Gala Awards), Arjun was the '''''WINNER''''' and his work received the '''''BEST OF SHOW''''' ''title as-well'''''.''' \n\nArjun received '''''2 Honourable Mentions''''' at the '''[https://px3.fr/ PX3 Paris],''' a total of '''''9 Honourable Mentions''''' at the '''IPA([https://www.colorawards.com/ International Color Awards])''', and '''''2 Nominations''''' at the '''International Photography Master\u2019s Cup'''.\n\n== Personal Life ==\nArjun is an avid [[Sport Fishing|sport-fishing]] enthusiast<ref name=\":10\" />, and an ardent [[Ocean life]] and [[Wildlife]] lover. \n\n== External Links ==\n[http://www.arjunmark.com Official website] of Arjun Mark \n\n[https://www.femina.in/fashion/fashion-news/four-established-professionals-share-their-success-mantras-129354-1.html Femina July 2019 Issue] - Four established professional share their success mantras\n\n[https://www.thepeacockmagazine.com/photographer-in-focus-arjun-mark/ Peacock Magazine Interview] - PHOTOGRAPHER IN FOCUS: ARJUN MARK\n\n[https://www.hindustantimes.com/art-and-culture/world-photography-day-top-indian-photographers-share-their-iconic-pics/story-fjkVDxUVUr7UNcbWkV5YGM.html HindustanTimes News Article] - Top Indian photographers on World Photography Day\n\n[https://www.glamflame.net/photography/top-8-fashion-photographers-of-india-in-2018/ Online Blog] - Top 8 Fashion Photographers Of India In 2018\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "name_user": "I.leslee", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arjun_Mark"}
{"title_page": "Trick of the Eye", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Trick of the Eye\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{hlist|Mystery|Thriller}}\n| based_on             = ''Trick of the Eye'' (novel) by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]\n| writer               = [[John Gay (screenwriter)|John Gay]]<br>[[Ken and Jim Wheat]]\n| director             = Ed Kaplan\n| starring             = [[Ellen Burstyn]]<br>[[Meg Tilly]]<br>[[Paxton Whitehead]]<br>[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]]<br>[[Barnard Hughes]]\n| music                = [[Allyn Ferguson]] \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| producer             = [[David A. Rosemont]]<br>[[Brent Shields]]\n| executive_producer   = Richard Welsh\n| location             = [[Pasadena, California]]\n| editor               = Sabrina Plisco-Morris\n| cinematography       = [[Shelly Johnson (cinematographer)|Shelly Johnson]]\n| runtime              = 95 minutes\n| company              = Signboard Hill Productions<br>[[Sonar Entertainment|Hallmark Entertainment]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = CBS\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1994|10|23}}\n| last_aired           = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Trick of the Eye''''' (also known as '''''Primal Secrets''''') is a 1994 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[psychological thriller|psychological thriller film]] starring [[Ellen Burstyn]] and [[Meg Tilly]]. Directed by Ed Kaplan, it is based on the 1992 novel of the same name by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]. The film originally premiered on [[CBS]] as a presentation of ''CBS Sunday Afternoon Showcase'' on October 23, 1994.\n\n==Plot==\nFaith Crowell (Meg Tilly) is a struggling bohemian artist who is commissioned to paint a mural for wealthy, reclusive socialite widow Frances Griffin (Ellen Burstyn). Frances wants Faith to paint murals all over the ornate walls of the abandoned ballroom of her ostentatious 211-acre estate. The theme of the mural is to be the grand entrance of Frances' daughter Cassandra at her debutante ball, which also happens to be the night Cassandra mysteriously died.\n\nFaith soon begins receiving expensive gifts from Frances, which she enjoys but doesn't understand why. Before long, Faith starts picking up on several uncanny resemblances between herself and the dead Cassandra. Eventually, she is invited to live in Frances' mansion until the mural is complete, and she discovers a painting of Cassandra and sees the haunting resemblance.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ellen Burstyn]] as Frances Griffin\n*[[Meg Tilly]] as Faith Crowell\n*[[Paxton Whitehead]] as Deane\n*[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]] as Simon\n*[[Romy Rosemont]] as Cathy Newman\n*[[Barnard Hughes]] as Harry Pitt\n\n==Production==\nThe film was shot from August 8 to August 31, 1994 at [[Huntington Library]] in [[Pasadena, California]]\n\n==Home video releases==\nIn July 1995, the film was released under the new title ''Primal Secrets'' on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] by [[Crown Media Holdings|Hallmark Home Entertainment]] and [[RLJE Films|Image Entertainment]].\n\nOn January 25, 2010, it was released as ''Primal Secrets'' on [[DVD]] by [[Echo Bridge Home Entertainment]].\n\n==References==\n#[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/475633/Trick-of-the-Eye/misc-notes.html Trick of the Eye: Miscellaneous Notes] at [[Turner Classic Movies|TCM]] (1994).\n#[https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-trick-of-the-eye-vol-42-no-17/ Picks and Pans Review: Trick of the Eye] by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine (October 24, 1994).\n#[https://www.lddb.com/laserdisc/06525/ID3185HL/Primal-Secrets-(Trick-of-the-Eye) Trick of the Eye] at LaserDisc Database (1995)\n#[https://www.amazon.com/Primal-Secrets-Ellen-Burstyn/dp/B0009ETCYC/ref=sr_1_9?dchild=1&keywords=primal+secrets&qid=1587029441&s=movies-tv&sr=1-9 ''Trick of the Eye'' (Primal Secrets)] at [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0111490|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{tcmdb title|475633|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{Amg movie|178294|Trick of the Eye}}\n\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:1994 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s mystery films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:CBS network films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n\n{{US-tv-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Trick of the Eye\n| image                = \n| image_size           = \n| image_alt            = \n| caption              = \n| genre                = {{hlist|Mystery|Thriller}}\n| based_on             = ''Trick of the Eye'' (novel) by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]\n| writer               = [[John Gay (screenwriter)|John Gay]]<br>[[Ken and Jim Wheat]]\n| director             = Ed Kaplan\n| starring             = [[Ellen Burstyn]]<br>[[Meg Tilly]]<br>[[Paxton Whitehead]]<br>[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]]<br>[[Barnard Hughes]]\n| music                = [[Allyn Ferguson]] \n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| producer             = [[David A. Rosemont]]<br>[[Brent Shields]]\n| executive_producer   = Richard Welsh\n| location             = [[Pasadena, California]]\n| editor               = Sabrina Plisco-Morris\n| cinematography       = [[Shelly Johnson (cinematographer)|Shelly Johnson]]\n| runtime              = 95 minutes\n| company              = Signboard Hill Productions<br>[[Sonar Entertainment|Hallmark Entertainment]]\n| distributor          = [[CBS]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = CBS\n| picture_format       = Color\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{start date|1994|10|23}}\n| last_aired           = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Trick of the Eye''''' (also known as '''''Primal Secrets''''') is a 1994 American [[television film|made-for-television]] [[psychological thriller|psychological thriller film]] starring [[Ellen Burstyn]] and [[Meg Tilly]]. Directed by Ed Kaplan, it is based on the 1992 novel of the same name by [[Jane Stanton Hitchcock]]. The film originally premiered on [[CBS]] as a presentation of ''CBS Sunday Afternoon Showcase'' on October 23, 1994.\n\n==Plot==\nFaith Crowell (Meg Tilly) is a struggling bohemian artist who is commissioned to paint a mural for wealthy, reclusive socialite widow Frances Griffin (Ellen Burstyn). Frances wants Faith to paint murals all over the ornate walls of the abandoned ballroom of her ostentatious 211-acre estate. The theme of the mural is to be the grand entrance of Frances' daughter Cassandra at her debutante ball, which also happens to be the night Cassandra mysteriously died.\n\nFaith soon begins receiving expensive gifts from Frances, which she enjoys but doesn't understand why. Before long, Faith starts picking up on several uncanny resemblances between herself and the dead Cassandra. Eventually, she is invited to live in Frances' mansion until the mural is complete, and she discovers a painting of Cassandra and sees the haunting resemblance.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Ellen Burstyn]] as Frances Griffin\n*[[Meg Tilly]] as Faith Crowell\n*[[Paxton Whitehead]] as Deane\n*[[Alastair Duncan (actor)|Alastair Duncan]] as Simon\n*[[Romy Rosemont]] as Cathy Newman\n*[[Barnard Hughes]] as Harry Pitt\n\n==Production==\nThe film was shot from August 8 to August 31, 1994 at [[Huntington Library]] in [[Pasadena, California]]\n\n==Home video releases==\nIn July 1995, the film was released under the new title ''Primal Secrets'' on [[VHS]] and [[LaserDisc]] by [[Crown Media Holdings|Hallmark Home Entertainment]] and [[RLJE Films|Image Entertainment]].\n\nOn January 25, 201, it was released as ''Primal Secrets'' on [[DVD]] by [[Echo Bridge Home Entertainment]].\n\n==References==\n#[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/475633/Trick-of-the-Eye/misc-notes.html Trick of the Eye: Miscellaneous Notes] at [[Turner Classic Movies|TCM]] (1994).\n#[https://people.com/archive/picks-and-pans-review-trick-of-the-eye-vol-42-no-17/ Picks and Pans Review: Trick of the Eye] by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine (October 24, 1994).\n#[https://www.lddb.com/laserdisc/06525/ID3185HL/Primal-Secrets-(Trick-of-the-Eye) Trick of the Eye] at LaserDisc Database (1995)\n#[https://www.amazon.com/Primal-Secrets-Ellen-Burstyn/dp/B0009ETCYC/ref=sr_1_9?dchild=1&keywords=primal+secrets&qid=1587029441&s=movies-tv&sr=1-9 ''Trick of the Eye'' (Primal Secrets)] at [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0111490|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{tcmdb title|475633|Trick of the Eye}}\n*{{Amg movie|178294|Trick of the Eye}}\n\n[[Category:1994 films]]\n[[Category:1994 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1990s mystery films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American mystery films]]\n[[Category:CBS network films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in California]]\n\n{{US-tv-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHome video releases", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trick_of_the_Eye"}
{"title_page": "Nelson Lichtenstein", "text_new": "{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = <!-- see [[MOS:CREDENTIAL]] and [[MOS:HONORIFIC]] -->\n| name               = Nelson Lichtenstein\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}  -->\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| region             = \n| nationality        = \n| citizenship        = \n| residence          = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = \n| period             = \n| known_for          = \n| home_town          = \n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            =\n| relatives          =\n| awards             = <!--notable national level awards only-->\n| website            = \n| education          = [[PhD]]\n| alma_mater         = <!--will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution-->\n| thesis_title       = Industrial unionism under the no-strike pledge: a study of the CIO during the Second World War<ref name=diss>{{cite thesis |last=Lichtenstein |first=Nelson |date=1974 |title=Industrial unionism under the no-strike pledge: a study of the CIO during the Second World War |type=PhD |chapter= |publisher= |docket= |oclc=229038098 |id={{ProQuest|302709298}} }}</ref>\n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = 1974\n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = <!--major academic discipline \u2013 e.g. Physicist, Sociologist, New Testament scholar, Ancient Near Eastern Linguist-->\n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = <!--full-time positions only, not student positions-->\n| doctoral_students  = [[Jennifer Klein (academic)|Jennifer Klein]]<ref name=disssuper>{{cite book |last=Klein |first=Jennifer |date=2003 |title=For All These Rights: Business, Labor, and the Shaping of America's Public-Private Welfare State |url=https://archive.org/details/foralltheseright0000klei |location=Princeton |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |page=x |isbn=0691126054 |author-link= }}</ref>, [[Meg Jacobs]]<ref name=jacobsdiss>{{cite thesis |last=Jacobs |first=Meg |date=1998 |title=The politics of purchasing power: Political economy, consumption politics, and state-building, 1909-1959 |type=PhD |chapter= |publisher= |docket= |oclc=44185250 |id={{ProQuest|304459366}} }}</ref> \n| notable_students   = \n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n\n'''Nelson Lichtenstein''' (born November 15, 1944) is a professor of [[history]] at the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]], and director of the [[Center for the Study of Work, Labor and Democracy]].<ref>[http://www.history.ucsb.edu/people/person.php?account_id=39  Nelson Lichtenstein UCSB Page]</ref>  He is [[Labor history (discipline)|labor historian]] who has written also about 20th-century [[United States|American]] [[political economy]], including the [[automotive industry]] and [[Wal-Mart]].\n\n==Life and education==\nLichtenstein received his [[bachelor's degree]] from [[Dartmouth College]] in 1966 and his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in history from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1974.<ref>[http://www.dartmouth.edu/~history/newsletter/Fall09/lichtenstein.html Dartmouth Department of History Newsletter]</ref> He is MacArthur Foundation Chair in History at  [[University of California, Santa Barbara|UCSB]].\n\n==Awards==\nLichtenstein was named a junior fellow by the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]] (NEH) in 1982 and senior NEH fellow in 1993.  He received a [[Rockefeller Foundation]] Fellowship to undertake research at [[Wayne State University]] in 1990. He held a Guggenheim Fellowship in 1997-98. He was elected to membership in the Society of American Historians in 2007 and became MacArthur Foundation Professor of History at UC Santa Barbara in 2010.\n\nLichtenstein's book ''State of the Union: A Century of American Labor'' won the [[Philip Taft Labor History Book Award]] in 2003. The Sidney Hillman Foundation awarded him the Sol Stetin Prize in 2012\n\n==Books==\n\n===Solely authored works===\n*''Walter Reuther, The Most Dangerous Man in Detroit.''  Urbana, Ill.: University of Illinois Press, 1997. {{ISBN|0-252-06626-X}}  [https://archive.org/details/walterreuthermos00lich <!-- quote=nelson lichtenstein. -->  Internet Archive link]\n*''Labor's War at Home: The CIO in World War II.'' Philadelphia: Temple University Press, 2003. {{ISBN|1-59213-197-2}}  [https://books.google.com/books?id=Qf83AAAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=nelson+lichtenstein&cd=3#v=onepage&q&f=false  Google Books link]\n*''State of the Union: A Century of American Labor.'' New edition. Princeton, N.J.: Princeton University Press, 2003. {{ISBN|0-691-11654-7}}  [https://books.google.com/books?id=7IFNKs_2zOIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=nelson+lichtenstein&cd=1#v=onepage&q&f=false Google Books link]\n*''The Retail Revolution: How Wal-Mart Created a Brave New World of Business.''New York: Henry Holt and Company, 2009. {{ISBN|0-8050-7966-1}}\n\n===Co-authored works===\n*''Who Built America? Vol. 2: 1865 to the Present,'' with Roy Rosenzweig and Joshua Brown. Boston: Bedford Books, 2007.\n\n===Edited works===\n*''Industrial Democracy in America,'' co-edited with Harris Howell John. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1993.\n*''Major Problems in the History of American Workers,'' with Eileen Boris.  Houghton Mifflin, 2002.\n*''American Capitalism: Social Thought and Political Economy in the Twentieth Century.'' Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 2006. {{ISBN|0-8122-3923-7}}  [https://books.google.com/books?id=e2XEt84peRsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=nelson+lichtenstein&source=bl&ots=XwZKTEnHdl&sig=ony1w_CDiCgPHUVM3hpaB3n3WOk&hl=en&ei=tvPXS6zALNyf-Abm2oyGBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CBYQ6AEwBDgK#v=onepage&q&f=false  Google Books link]\n*''Wal-Mart: The Face of Twenty-First-Century Capitalism.'' New York: The New Press, 2005. Cloth {{ISBN|1-59558-035-2}}; Paperback {{ISBN|1-59558-021-2}}\n*''The Right and Labor in America: Politics, Ideology, and Imagination'', co-edited with Elizabeth Tandy Shermer. Philadelphia: University of Pennsylvania Press, 2012.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*''Who's Who in the South and Southwest.'' 24th ed. New Providence, N.J.: Marquis Who's Who, 2002.\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.history.ucsb.edu/people/person.php?account_id=39 Nelson Lichtenstein UCSB Faculty homepage]\n*[http://inthesetimes.com/inperson/4511/nelson_lichtenstein/ \"Twenty Questions with Nelson Lichtenstein,\" ''In These Times'']\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=111843210 NPR interview with Lichtenstein on Wal-Mart, 2009]\n*[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=1151369&ps=rs NPR interview with Lichtenstein about Taft-Hartley Act, 2002]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lichtenstein, Nelson}}\n[[Category:20th-century American historians]]\n[[Category:Historians of the United States]]\n[[Category:Labor historians]]\n[